# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mitre-attack
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] An **advanced persistent threat** (**APT**) is a stealthy cybersecurity threat, typically manipulated by a state or state-sponsored group, which gains unauthorized access to a computer network and remains undetected for an extended period.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] In recent times, the term may also refer to non-state-sponsored groups conducting large-scale targeted intrusions for specific goals.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] Such threat actors' motivations are typically political or economic.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] Every major business sector has recorded instances of cyberattacks by advanced actors with specific goals, whether to steal, spy, or disrupt.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] These targeted sectors include government, defense, financial services, legal services, industrial, telecoms, consumer goods and many more.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] Some groups utilize traditional espionage vectors, including social engineering, human intelligence and infiltration to gain access to a physical location to enable network attacks.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] The purpose of these attacks is to install custom malware.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] APT attacks on mobile devices have also become a legitimate concern, since attackers are able to penetrate into cloud and mobile infrastructure to eavesdrop, steal, and tamper with data.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] The median "dwell-time", the time an APT attack goes undetected, differs widely between regions.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] FireEye reported the mean dwell-time for 2018 in the Americas as 71 days, EMEA as 177 days, and APAC as 204 days.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] Such a long dwell-time allows attackers a significant amount of time to go through the attack cycle, propagate, and achieve their objectives.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] Warnings against targeted, socially-engineered emails dropping trojans to exfiltrate sensitive information were published by UK and US CERT organisations in 2005.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] This method was used throughout the early 1990s and does not in itself constitute an APT.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] The term "advanced persistent threat" has been cited as originating from the United States Air Force in 2006 with Colonel Greg Rattray cited as the individual who coined the term.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] The Stuxnet computer worm, which targeted the computer hardware of Iran's nuclear program, is one example of an APT attack.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] In this case, the Iranian government might consider the Stuxnet creators to be an advanced persistent threat.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] Advanced persistent threat (APT) as a term may be shifting focus to computer-based hacking due to the rising number of occurrences.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] PC World reported an 81 percent increase from 2010 to 2011 of particularly advanced targeted computer attacks.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] Actors in many countries have used cyberspace as a means to gather intelligence on individuals and groups of individuals of interest.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] The United States Cyber Command is tasked with coordinating the US military's offensive and defensive cyber operations.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] Numerous sources have alleged that some APT groups are affiliated with, or are agents of, governments of sovereign states.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] A Bell Canada study provided deep research into the anatomy of APTs and uncovered widespread presence in Canadian government and critical infrastructure.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] Attribution was established to Chinese and Russian actors.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] In incidents analysed by Mandiant, the average period over which the attackers controlled the victim's network was one year, with longest – almost five years.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] The infiltrations were allegedly performed by Shanghai-based Unit 61398 of People's Liberation Army.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] Chinese officials have denied any involvement in these attacks.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] Previous reports from Secdev had previously discovered and implicated Chinese actors.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] There are tens of millions of malware variations, which makes it extremely challenging to protect organizations from APT.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] While APT activities are stealthy and hard to detect, the command and control network traffic associated with APT can be detected at the network layer level with sophisticated methods.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] Deep log analyses and log correlation from various sources is of limited usefulness in detecting APT activities.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] It is challenging to separate noises from legitimate traffic.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] Traditional security technology and methods have been ineffective in detecting or mitigating APTs.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] Active cyber defense has yielded greater efficacy in detecting and prosecuting APTs (find, fix, finish) when applying cyber threat intelligence to hunt and adversary pursuit activities.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] Human-Introduced Cyber Vulnerabilities (HICV) are a weak cyber link that are neither well understood nor mitigated, constituting a significant attack vector.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] Multiple organizations may assign different names to the same actor.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] As separate researchers could each have their own varying assessments of an APT group, companies such as CrowdStrike, Kaspersky, Mandiant, and Microsoft, among others, have their own internal naming schemes.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] Names between different organizations may refer to overlapping but ultimately different groups, based on various data gathered.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] CrowdStrike assigns animals by nation-state or other category, such as "Kitten" for Iran and "Spider" for groups focused on cybercrime.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] Other companies have named groups based on this system — Rampant Kitten, for instance, was named by Check Point rather than CrowdStrike.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] Dragos bases its names for APT groups on minerals.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] Mandiant assigns numbered acronyms in three categories, APT, FIN, and UNC, resulting in APT names like FIN7.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] Other companies using a similar system include Proofpoint (TA) and IBM (ITG and Hive).
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] Microsoft used to assign names from the periodic table, often stylized in all-caps (e.g.
[src:mitre-attack/advanced-persistent-threat] POTASSIUM); in April 2023, Microsoft changed its naming schema to use weather-based names (e.g.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] The **cyber kill chain** is the process by which perpetrators carry out cyberattacks.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] Lockheed Martin adapted the concept of the *kill chain* from a military setting to information security, using it as a method for modeling intrusions on a computer network.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] The cyber kill chain model has seen some adoption in the information security community.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] However, acceptance is not universal, with critics pointing to what they believe are fundamental flaws in the model.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] Computer scientists at Lockheed-Martin corporation described a new "intrusion kill chain" framework or model to defend computer networks in 2011.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] They wrote that attacks may occur in phases and can be disrupted through controls established at each phase.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] Since then, the "cyber kill chain" has been adopted by data security organizations to define phases of cyberattacks.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] A cyber kill chain reveals the phases of a cyberattack: from early reconnaissance to the goal of data exfiltration.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] The kill chain can also be used as a management tool to help continuously improve network defense.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] Weaponization: Intruder creates remote access malware weapon, such as a virus or worm, tailored to one or more vulnerabilities.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] Exploitation: Malware weapon's program code triggers, which takes action on target network to exploit vulnerability.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] Installation: Malware weapon installs an access point (e.g., "backdoor") usable by the intruder.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] Command and Control: Malware enables intruder to have "hands on the keyboard" persistent access to the target network.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] Actions on Objective: Intruder takes action to achieve their goals, such as data exfiltration, data destruction, or encryption for ransom.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] Deny: Prevent information disclosure and unauthorized access.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] Disrupt: Stop or change outbound traffic (to attacker).
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] Degrade: Counter-attack command and control.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] Deceive: Interfere with command and control.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] Senate investigation of the 2013 Target Corporation data breach included analysis based on the Lockheed-Martin kill chain framework.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] It identified several stages where controls did not prevent or detect progression of the attack.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] Different organizations have constructed their own kill chains to try to model different threats.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] FireEye proposes a linear model similar to Lockheed-Martin's.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] In FireEye's kill chain the persistence of threats is emphasized.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] This model stresses that a threat does not end after one cycle.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] Initial Intrusion: Once the attacker has gathered enough information, they attempt to breach the target system or network.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] This could involve exploiting vulnerabilities in software or systems, utilizing social engineering techniques to trick users, or using other methods to gain initial access.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] Establish a Backdoor: After gaining initial access, the attacker often creates a backdoor or a persistent entry point into the compromised system.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] This ensures that even if the initial breach is discovered and mitigated, the attacker can still regain access.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] Obtain User Credentials: With a foothold in the system, the attacker may attempt to steal user credentials.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] This can involve techniques like keylogging, phishing, or exploiting weak authentication mechanisms.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] Install Various Utilities: Attackers may install various tools, utilities, or malware on the compromised system to facilitate further movement, data collection, or control.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] These tools could include remote access Trojans (RATs), keyloggers, and other types of malicious software.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] Privilege Escalation / Lateral Movement / Data Exfiltration: Once inside the system, the attacker seeks to elevate their privileges to gain more control over the network.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] They might move laterally within the network, trying to access more valuable systems or sensitive data.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] Data exfiltration involves stealing and transmitting valuable information out of the network.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] Maintain Persistence: This stage emphasizes the attacker's goal to maintain a long-term presence within the compromised environment.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] They do this by continuously evading detection, updating their tools, and adapting to any security measures put in place.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] Among the critiques of Lockheed Martin's cyber kill chain model as threat assessment and prevention tool is that the first phases happen outside the defended network, making it difficult to identify or defend against actions in these phases.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] Similarly, this methodology is said to reinforce traditional perimeter-based and malware prevention-based defensive strategies.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] Others have noted that the traditional cyber kill chain isn't suitable to model the insider threat.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] This is particularly troublesome given the likelihood of successful attacks that breach the internal network perimeter, which is why organizations "need to develop a strategy for dealing with attackers inside the firewall.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] They need to think of every attacker as [a] potential insider".
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] The unified version of the kill chain is an ordered arrangement of 18 unique attack phases that may occur in an end-to-end cyberattack, which covers activities that occur outside and within the defended network.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] As such, the unified kill chain improves over the scope limitations of the traditional kill chain and the time-agnostic nature of tactics in MITRE's ATT&CK.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] The unified model can be used to analyze, compare, and defend against end-to-end cyberattacks by advanced persistent threats.
[src:mitre-attack/cyber-kill-chain] A subsequent whitepaper on the unified kill chain was published in 2021.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] In computer science, a **cyberattack** (or **cyber attack**) is an attack targeted at computer systems.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] It occurs when there is an unauthorized action against computer infrastructure that compromises the confidentiality, integrity, or availability of its content.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] The rising dependence on increasingly complex and interconnected computer systems in most domains of life is the main factor that causes vulnerability to cyberattacks, since virtually all computer systems have bugs that can be exploited by attackers.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Although it is impossible or impractical to create a perfectly secure system, there are many defense mechanisms that can make a system more difficult to attack, making information security a field of rapidly increasing importance in the world today.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Perpetrators of a cyberattack can be criminals, hacktivists, or states.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] They attempt to find weaknesses in a system, exploit them and create malware to carry out their goals, and deliver it to the targeted system.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Once installed, the malware can have a variety of effects depending on its purpose.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Detection of cyberattacks is often absent or delayed, especially when the malware attempts to spy on the system while remaining undiscovered.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] If it is discovered, the targeted organization may attempt to collect evidence about the attack, remove malware from its systems, and close the vulnerability that enabled the attack.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Cyberattacks can cause a variety of harms to targeted individuals, organizations, and governments, including significant financial losses and identity theft.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] They are usually illegal both as a method of crime and warfare, although correctly attributing the attack is difficult and perpetrators are rarely prosecuted.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] A cyberattack is any attempt by an individual or organization to use computers or digital systems to steal, alter, expose, disable, or destroy information, or to breach computer systems, networks, or infrastructures.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Definitions differ as to the type of compromise required – for example, requiring the system to produce unexpected responses or cause injury or property damage.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Some definitions exclude attacks carried out by non-state actors and others require the target to be a state.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Keeping a system secure relies on maintaining the CIA triad: confidentiality (no unauthorized access), integrity (no unauthorized modification), and availability.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Although availability is less important for some web-based services, it can be the most crucial aspect for industrial systems.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] In the first six months of 2017, two billion data records were stolen or impacted by cyber attacks, and ransomware payments reached US$2 billion, double that in 2016.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] In 2020, with the increase of remote work as an effect of the COVID-19 global pandemic, cybersecurity statistics reveal a huge increase in hacked and breached data.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] The worldwide information security market is forecast to reach $170.4 billion in 2022.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Over time, computer systems make up an increasing portion of daily life and interactions.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] While the increasing complexity and connectedness of the systems increases the efficiency, power, and convenience of computer technology, it also renders the systems more vulnerable to attack and worsens the consequences of an attack, should one occur.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Despite developers' goal of delivering a product that works entirely as intended, virtually all software and hardware contains bugs.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] If a bug creates a security risk, it is called a vulnerability.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Patches are often released to fix identified vulnerabilities, but those that remain unknown (zero days) as well as those that have not been patched are still liable for exploitation.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] The software vendor is not legally liable for the cost if a vulnerability is used in an attack, which creates an incentive to make cheaper but less secure software.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Vulnerabilities vary in their ability to be exploited by malicious actors.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] The most valuable allow the attacker to inject and run their own code (called malware), without the user being aware of it.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Without a vulnerability enabling access, the attacker cannot gain access to the system.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] The Vulnerability Model (VM) identifies attack patterns, threats, and valuable assets, which can be physical or intangible.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] It addresses security concerns like confidentiality, integrity, availability, and accountability within business, application, or infrastructure contexts.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] A system's architecture and design decisions play a major role in determining how safe it can be.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] The traditional approach to improving security is the detection of systems vulnerable to attack and hardening these systems to make attacks more difficult, but it is only partially effective.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Formal risk assessment for compromise of highly complex and interconnected systems is impractical and the related question of how much to spend on security is difficult to answer.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Because of the ever changing and uncertain nature of cyber-threats, risk assessment may produce scenarios that are costly or unaffordable to mitigate.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] As of 2019, there are no commercially available, widely used active defense systems for protecting systems by intentionally increasing the complexity or variability of systems to make it harder to attack.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] The cyber resilience approach, on the other hand, assumes that breaches will occur and focuses on protecting essential functionality even if parts are compromised, using approaches such as micro-segmentation, zero trust, and business continuity planning.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] The majority of attacks can be prevented by ensuring all software is fully patched.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Nevertheless, fully patched systems are still vulnerable to exploits using zero-day vulnerabilities.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] The highest risk of attack occurs just after a vulnerability has been publicly disclosed or a patch is released, because attackers can create exploits faster than a patch can be developed and rolled out.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Software solutions aim to prevent unauthorized access and detect the intrusion of malicious software.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Training users can avoid cyberattacks (for example, not to click on a suspicious link or email attachment), especially those that depend on user error.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] However, too many rules can cause employees to disregard them, negating any security improvement.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Some insider attacks can also be prevented using rules and procedures.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] There is little evidence about the effectiveness and cost-effectiveness of different cyberattack prevention measures.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Although attention to security can reduce the risk of attack, achieving perfect security for a complex system is impossible, and many security measures have unacceptable cost or usability downsides.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] For example, reducing the complexity and functionality of the system is effective at reducing the attack surface.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Disconnecting systems from the internet is one truly effective measure against attacks, but it is rarely feasible.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] In some jurisdictions, there are legal requirements for protecting against attacks.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] The cyber kill chain is the process by which perpetrators carry out cyberattacks.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Weaponization: after finding a vulnerability, attackers build an exploit to gain access, and malware to carry out the attack.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Delivery: once complete, the malware is delivered to the target.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Most data breaches and malware insertions are enabled by phishing, where the attacker sends a malicious communication, often an email, in an attempt to get the recipient to click on a link or attachment to deliver malware.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Drive-by-download does not require any clicks, only a visit to a malicious website.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Sometimes insiders are behind the attack and can use their credentials to bypass security.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Some attacks are delivered indirectly via associated companies that have a business relationship with the target.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Others may be delivered by directly accessing hardware, particularly in the cases of bribery or blackmail.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Exploitation: the attacker's software is executed on the targeted system, and often creates a backdoor to enable remote control by the attacker.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Many attackers will not launch an attack right away.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] The attacker often seeks to persist after system interruption (such as crash or restart), evade detection, and escalate privileges, and secure multiple channels of communication with its controllers.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Other common actions include responding to remote controls and collecting and copying data to a device controlled by the attacker (data exfiltration).
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] After the malware is installed, its activity varies greatly depending on the attacker's goals.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Many attackers try to eavesdrop on a system without affecting it.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Although this type of malware can have unexpected side effects, it is often very difficult to detect.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Botnets are networks of compromised devices that can be used to send spam or carry out denial-of-service attacks—flooding a system with too many requests for the system to handle at once, causing it to become unusable.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Attackers may also use computers to mine cryptocurrencies, such as Bitcoin, for their own profit.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Ransomware is software used to encrypt or destroy data; attackers demand payment for the restoration of the targeted system.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] The advent of cryptocurrency enabling anonymous transactions has led to a dramatic increase in ransomware demands.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] The stereotype of a hacker is an individual working for one's self.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] However, many cyber threats are teams of well-resourced experts.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] "Growing revenues for cyber criminals are leading to more and more attacks, increasing professionalism and highly specialized attackers.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] In addition, unlike other forms of crime, cybercrime can be carried out remotely, and cyber attacks often scale well." Many cyberattacks are caused or enabled by insiders, often employees who bypass security procedures to get their job done more efficiently.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Attackers vary widely in their skill and sophistication and well as their determination to attack a particular target, as opposed to opportunistically picking one easy to attack.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] The skill level of the attacker determined which types of attacks they are prepared to mount.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] The most sophisticated attackers can persist undetected on a hardened system for an extended period of time.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Depending whether the expected threat is passive espionage, data manipulation, or active hijacking, different mitigation methods may be needed.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Software vendors and governments are mainly interested in undisclosed vulnerabilities (zero-days), while organized crime groups are more interested in ready-to-use exploit kits based on known vulnerabilities, which are much cheaper.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] The lack of transparency in the market causes problems, such as buyers being unable to guarantee that the zero-day vulnerability was not sold to another party.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Both buyers and sellers advertise on the dark web and use cryptocurrency for untraceable transactions.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Because of the difficulty in writing and maintaining software that can attack a wide variety of systems, criminals found they could make more money by renting out their exploits rather than using them directly.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Cybercrime as a service, where hackers sell prepacked software that can be used to cause a cyberattack, is increasingly popular as a lower risk and higher profit activity than traditional hacking.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] A major form of this is to create a botnet of compromised devices and rent or sell it to another cybercriminal.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Different botnets are equipped for different tasks such as DDOS attacks or password cracking.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] It is also possible to buy the software used to create a botnet and bots that load the purchaser's malware onto a botnet's devices.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] DDOS as a service using botnets retained under the control of the seller is also common, and may be the first cybercrime as a service product, and can also be committed by SMS flooding on the cellular network.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Malware and ransomware as a service have made it possible for individuals without technical ability to carry out cyberattacks.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Targets of cyberattacks range from individuals to corporations and government entities.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Many cyberattacks are foiled or unsuccessful, but those that succeed can have devastating consequences.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Understanding the negative effects of cyberattacks helps organizations ensure that their prevention strategies are cost-effective.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Thousands of data records are stolen from individuals every day.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] According to a 2020 estimate, 55 percent of data breaches were caused by organized crime, 10 percent by system administrators, 10 percent by end users such as customers or employees, and 10 percent by states or state-affiliated actors.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Opportunistic criminals may cause data breaches—often using malware or social engineering attacks, but they will typically move on if the security is above average.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] More organized criminals have more resources and are more focused in their targeting of particular data.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Both of them sell the information they obtain for financial gain.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Another source of data breaches are politically motivated hackers, for example Anonymous, that target particular objectives.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] State-sponsored hackers target either citizens of their country or foreign entities, for such purposes as political repression and espionage.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] After a data breach, criminals make money by selling data, such as usernames, passwords, social media or customer loyalty account information, debit and credit card numbers, and personal health information (see medical data breach).
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] This information may be used for a variety of purposes, such as spamming, obtaining products with a victim's loyalty or payment information, prescription drug fraud, insurance fraud, and especially identity theft.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Consumer losses from a breach are usually a negative externality for the business.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Critical infrastructure is that considered most essential—such as healthcare, water supply, transport, and financial services—which has been increasingly governed by cyber-physical systems that depend on network access for their functionality.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] For years, writers have warned of cataclysmic consequences of cyberattacks that have failed to materialize as of 2023.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] These extreme scenarios could still occur, but many experts consider that it is unlikely that challenges in inflicting physical damage or spreading terror can be overcome.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Smaller-scale cyberattacks, sometimes resulting in interruption of essential services, regularly occur.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] There is little empirical evidence of economic harm (such as reputational damage) from breaches except the direct cost for such matters as legal, technical, and public relations recovery efforts.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Studies that have attempted to correlate cyberattacks to short-term declines in stock prices have found contradictory results, with some finding modest losses, others finding no effect, and some researchers criticizing these studies on methodological grounds.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] The effect on stock price may vary depending on the type of attack.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Some experts have argued that the evidence suggests there is not enough direct costs or reputational damage from breaches to sufficiently incentivize their prevention.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Government websites and services are among those affected by cyberattacks.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Some experts hypothesize that cyberattacks weaken societal trust or trust in the government, but as of 2023 this notion has only limited evidence.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Responding quickly to attacks is an effective way to limit the damage.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] The response is likely to require a wide variety of skills, from technical investigation to legal and public relations.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Because of the prevalence of cyberattacks, some companies plan their incident response before any attack is detected, and may designate a computer emergency response team to be prepared to handle incidents.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Of those that are, the average time to discovery is 197 days.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Some systems can detect and flag anomalies that may indicate an attack, using such technology as antivirus, firewall, or an intrusion detection system.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Once suspicious activity is suspected, investigators look for indicators of attack and indicators of compromise.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Discovery is quicker and more likely if the attack targets information availability (for example with a denial-of-service attack) rather than integrity (modifying data) or confidentiality (copying data without changing it).
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] State actors are more likely to keep the attack secret.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Sophisticated attacks using valuable exploits are more less likely to be detected or announced – as the perpetrator wants to protect the usefulness of the exploit.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Evidence collection is done immediately, prioritizing volatile evidence that is likely to be erased quickly.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Gathering data about the breach can facilitate later litigation or criminal prosecution, but only if the data is gathered according to legal standards and the chain of custody is maintained.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Containing the affected system is often a high priority after an attack, and may be enacted by shutoff, isolation, use of a sandbox system to find out more about the adversary patching the vulnerability, and rebuilding.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Once the exact way that the system was compromised is identified, there is typically only one or two technical vulnerabilities that need to be addressed in order to contain the breach and prevent it from reoccurring.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] A penetration test can then verify that the fix is working as expected.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] If malware is involved, the organization must investigate and close all infiltration and exfiltration vectors, as well as locate and remove all malware from its systems.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Containment can compromise investigation, and some tactics (such as shutting down servers) can violate the company's contractual obligations.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] After the breach is fully contained, the company can then work on restoring all systems to operational.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Maintaining a backup and having tested incident response procedures are used to improve recovery.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Attributing a cyberattack is difficult, and of limited interest to companies that are targeted by cyberattacks.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] In contrast, secret services often have a compelling interest in finding out whether a state is behind the attack.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Unlike attacks carried out in person, determining the entity behind a cyberattack is difficult.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] A further challenge in attribution of cyberattacks is the possibility of a false flag attack, where the actual perpetrator makes it appear that someone else caused the attack.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Every stage of the attack may leave artifacts, such as entries in log files, that can be used to help determine the attacker's goals and identity.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] In the aftermath of an attack, investigators often begin by saving as many artifacts as they can find, and then try to determine the attacker.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Law enforcement agencies may investigate cyber incidents although the hackers responsible are rarely caught.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Most states agree that cyberattacks are regulated under the laws governing the use of force in international law, and therefore cyberattacks as a form of warfare are likely to violate the prohibition of aggression.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Therefore, they could be prosecuted as a crime of aggression.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] There is also agreement that cyberattacks are governed by international humanitarian law, and if they target civilian infrastructure, they could be prosecuted as a war crime, crime against humanity, or act of genocide.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] International courts cannot enforce these laws without sound attribution of the attack, without which countermeasures by a state are not legal either.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] In many countries, cyberattacks are prosecutable under various laws aimed at cybercrime.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Attribution of the attack beyond reasonable doubt to the accused is also a major challenge in criminal proceedings.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] In 2021, United Nations member states began negotiating a draft cybercrime treaty.
[src:mitre-attack/cyberattack] Many jurisdictions have data breach notification laws that require organizations to notify people whose personal data has been compromised in a cyberattack.
[src:mitre-attack/groups] Groups are activity clusters that are tracked by a common name in the security community.
[src:mitre-attack/groups] Analysts track these clusters using various analytic methodologies and terms such as threat groups, activity groups, and threat actors.
[src:mitre-attack/groups] Some groups have multiple names associated with similar activities due to various organizations tracking similar activities by different names.
[src:mitre-attack/groups] Organizations' group definitions may partially overlap with groups designated by other organizations and may disagree on specific activity.
[src:mitre-attack/groups] For the purposes of the Group pages, the MITRE ATT&CK team uses the term Group to refer to any of the above designations for an adversary activity cluster.
[src:mitre-attack/groups] The team makes a best effort to track overlaps between names based on publicly reported associations, which are designated as “Associated Groups” on each page (formerly labeled “Aliases”), because we believe these overlaps are useful for analyst awareness.
[src:mitre-attack/groups] We do not represent these names as exact overlaps and encourage analysts to do additional research.
[src:mitre-attack/groups] Groups are mapped to publicly reported technique use and original references are included.
[src:mitre-attack/groups] The information provided does not represent all possible technique use by Groups, but rather a subset that is available solely through open source reporting.
[src:mitre-attack/groups] Groups are also mapped to reported Software used and attributed Campaigns, and related techniques for each are tracked separately on their respective pages.
[src:mitre-attack/mitigations-enterprise] Mitigations represent security concepts and classes of technologies that can be used to prevent a technique or sub-technique from being successfully executed.
[src:mitre-attack/mitre-att-ck] The **Adversarial Tactics, Techniques, and Common Knowledge** (**ATT&CK**) is a guideline for classifying and describing cyberattacks and intrusions.
[src:mitre-attack/mitre-att-ck] It was created by the Mitre Corporation and released in 2013.
[src:mitre-attack/mitre-att-ck] The MITRE ATT&CK framework is widely used within cybersecurity, because it is a public catalog of known attacker techniques, where every technique has an ID, such as "T1566-Phishing".
[src:mitre-attack/mitre-att-ck] It gives the industry a shared vocabulary: an analyst can write the ID in a report and every reader will know exactly what is meant.
[src:mitre-attack/mitre-att-ck] The US Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency's (CISA) formally recognised the importance of this framework in "Best practices for Mitre ATT&CK mapping", cementing its status as government-endorsed for the standardization of threat intelligence work.
[src:mitre-attack/mitre-att-ck] Rather than examining the results of an attack (also known as indicators of compromise (IoCs)), it identifies tactics that indicate an attack is in progress.
[src:mitre-attack/mitre-att-ck] Tactics are the “why” of an attack technique.
[src:mitre-attack/mitre-att-ck] The framework consisted in 2022 of 14 tactic categories, which encompass the methods of an adversary.
[src:mitre-attack/mitre-att-ck] Examples include privilege escalation and command and control.
[src:mitre-attack/mitre-att-ck] These categories are then broken down further into specific techniques and sub-techniques.
[src:mitre-attack/mitre-att-ck] In the latest release of the framework, ATT&CK version 19 released in April 2026, there are now 15 Tactic categories.
[src:mitre-attack/mitre-att-ck] The previous "Defense Evasion" category has been split in 2: "Stealth" where defenses appear intact depite having been broken by adversaries and "Defense Impairment" capturing behavior where Defenses are actively and visibly broken.
[src:mitre-attack/mitre-att-ck] The framework is an alternative to the cyber kill chain developed by Lockheed Martin.
[src:mitre-attack/mitre-att-ck] The ATT&CK Matrix for Enterprise is a comprehensive framework that is presented as a kanban board-style diagram.
[src:mitre-attack/mitre-att-ck] It defined in 2022 14 categories of tactics, techniques and procedures (TTPs) used by cybercriminals with the associated techniques and sub-techniques.
[src:mitre-attack/mitre-att-ck] Reconnaissance is the initial stage of information gathering for an eventual cyberattack.
[src:mitre-attack/mitre-att-ck] There are 10 techniques – including the use of network scanning, social engineering and Open-source intelligence (OSINT).
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] OSINT, broadly defined, involves gathering and analyzing publicly accessible information to produce actionable insights.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] Department of Homeland Security defines OSINT as intelligence derived from publicly available information, collected and disseminated promptly to address specific intelligence needs.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] NATO describes OSINT as intelligence obtained from publicly available information and other unclassified data with limited public distribution or access.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] The European Union defines OSINT as the collecting and analyzing information from open sources to generate actionable intelligence, supporting areas like national security, law enforcement, and business intelligence.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] The United Nations has also recognized OSINT’s potential, noting its value in monitoring member states’ compliance with international regulations across various sectors, including public health and human rights.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] In the private sector, companies like IBM define OSINT as the process of gathering and analyzing publicly available information to assess threats, inform decisions, or answer specific questions.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] Similarly, cybersecurity firms such as CrowdStrike describe OSINT as the act of collecting and analyzing publicly available data for intelligence purposes.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] OSINT practices have been documented as early as the mid-19th century in the United States and early 20th century in the United Kingdom.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] OSINT in the United States traces its origins to the 1941 creation of the Foreign Broadcast Monitoring Service (FBMS), an agency responsible for the monitoring of foreign broadcasts.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] An example of their work was the correlation of changes in the price of oranges in Paris with successful bombings of railway bridges during World War II.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] The Aspin-Brown Commission stated in 1996 that US access to open sources was "severely deficient" and that this should be a "top priority" for both funding and DCI attention.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] In July 2004, following the September 11 attacks, the 9/11 Commission recommended the creation of an open-source intelligence agency.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] In March 2005, the Iraq Intelligence Commission recommended the creation of an open-source directorate at the CIA.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] Following these recommendations, in November 2005 the Director of National Intelligence announced the creation of the DNI Open Source Center.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] The Center was established to collect information available from "the Internet, databases, press, radio, television, video, geospatial data, photos and commercial imagery." In addition to collecting openly available information, it would train analysts to make better use of this information.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] The center absorbed the CIA's previously existing Foreign Broadcast Information Service (FBIS), originally established in 1941, with FBIS head Douglas Naquin named as director of the center.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] Then, following the events of 9/11 the Intelligence Reform and Terrorism Prevention Act merged FBIS and other research elements into the Office of the Director of National Intelligence creating the Open Source Enterprise.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] Furthermore, the private sector has invested in tools which aid in OSINT collection and analysis.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] Specifically, In-Q-Tel, a Central Intelligence Agency supported venture capital firm in Arlington, VA assisted companies develop web-monitoring and predictive analysis tools.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] In December 2005, the Director of National Intelligence appointed Eliot A.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] Jardines as the Assistant Deputy Director of National Intelligence for Open Source to serve as the Intelligence Community's senior intelligence officer for open source and to provide strategy, guidance and oversight for the National Open Source Enterprise.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] Jardines has established the National Open Source Enterprise and authored intelligence community directive 301.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] Jardines returned to the private sector and was succeeded by Dan Butler who is ADDNI/OS and previously Mr.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] OSINT is distinguished from research in that it applies the process of intelligence to create tailored knowledge supportive of a specific decision by a specific individual or group.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] A guide by Ryan Fedasiuk, an analyst at the Center for Security and Emerging Technology, lists six tools open-source analysts can use to stay safe and utilize operational security (OPSEC) when conducting online investigations.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] These include VPNs, cached webpages, digital archive services, URL and file scanners, browser sandbox applications, and antivirus software.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] Numerous lists of aggregated OSINT content are available on the web.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] The OSINT Framework contains over 30 primary categories of tools and is maintained as an open source project on GitHub.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] A main hindrance to practical OSINT is the volume of information it has to deal with information explosion.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] The amount of data being distributed increases at a rate that it becomes difficult to evaluate sources in intelligence analysis.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] To a small degree the work has sometimes been done by amateur crowd-sourcing.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] Private individuals illegally collecting data for a foreign military or intelligence agency is considered espionage in most countries.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] Espionage that is not treason (e.g. betraying one's country of citizenship) has been a tool of statecraft since ancient times.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] The open and accessible nature of public sources makes OSINT particularly vulnerable to contamination.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] Extremist groups regularly use OSINT to spread to misinformation and spread their ideology.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] Governments and state actors have been documented intentionally disseminating disinformation through public channels to influence perceptions, confuse adversaries, or undermine trust in open-source findings.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] This can include planting false information in news outlets, social media, official statements, or even manipulated geospatial data to deceive OSINT practitioners who rely on such sources.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] The OSINT Foundation is a professional association for OSINT practitioners in the United States Intelligence Community.
[src:mitre-attack/open-source-intelligence] Citizens and seeks to raise the prominence of the open-source intelligence discipline.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Software is a generic term for custom or commercial code, operating system utilities, open-source software, or other tools used to conduct behavior modeled in ATT&CK.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Some instances of software have multiple names associated with the same instance due to various organizations tracking the same set of software by different names.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] The team makes a best effort to track overlaps between names based on publicly reported associations, which are designated as “Associated Software” on each page (formerly labeled “Aliases”), because we believe these overlaps are useful for analyst awareness.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Software entries include publicly reported technique use or capability to use a technique and may be mapped to Groups who have been reported to use that Software.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] The information provided does not represent all possible technique use by a piece of Software, but rather a subset that is available solely through open source reporting.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] 3PARA RAT is a remote access tool (RAT) programmed in C++ that has been used by Putter Panda.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] 4H RAT is malware that has been used by Putter Panda since at least 2007.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] AADInternals is a PowerShell-based framework for administering, enumerating, and exploiting Azure Active Directory.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] The tool is publicly available on GitHub.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] ABK is a downloader that has been used by BRONZE BUTLER since at least 2019.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] AbstractEmu is mobile malware that was first seen in Google Play and other third-party stores in October 2021.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] It was discovered in 19 Android applications, of which at least 7 abused known Android exploits for obtaining root permissions.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] AbstractEmu was observed primarily impacting users in the United States, however victims are believed to be across a total of 17 countries.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] ACAD/Medre.A is a worm that steals operational information.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] The worm collects AutoCAD files with drawings.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] ACAD/Medre.A has the capability to be used for industrial espionage.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] AcidPour is a variant of AcidRain designed to impact a wider range of x86 architecture Linux devices.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] AcidPour is an x86 ELF binary that expands on the targeted devices and locations in AcidRain by including items such as Unsorted Block Image (UBI), Deice Mapper (DM), and various flash memory references.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Based on this expanded targeting, AcidPour can impact a variety of device types including IoT, networking, and ICS embedded device types.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] AcidPour is a wiping payload associated with the Sandworm Team threat actor, and potentially linked to attacks against Ukrainian internet service providers (ISPs) in 2023.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] AcidRain is an ELF binary targeting modems and routers using MIPS architecture.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] AcidRain is associated with the ViaSat KA-SAT communication outage that took place during the initial phases of the 2022 full-scale invasion of Ukraine.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Analysis indicates overlap with another network device-targeting malware, VPNFilter, associated with Sandworm Team.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] US and European government sources linked AcidRain to Russian government entities, while Ukrainian government sources linked AcidRain specifically to Sandworm Team.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Action RAT is a remote access tool written in Delphi that has been used by SideCopy since at least December 2021 against Indian and Afghani government personnel.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] adbupd is a backdoor used by PLATINUM that is similar to Dipsind.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] AdFind is a free command-line query tool that can be used for gathering information from Active Directory.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Adups is software that was pre-installed onto Android devices, including those made by BLU Products.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] The software was reportedly designed to help a Chinese phone manufacturer monitor user behavior, transferring sensitive data to a Chinese server.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] ADVSTORESHELL is a spying backdoor that has been used by APT28 from at least 2012 to 2016.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] It is generally used for long-term espionage and is deployed on targets deemed interesting after a reconnaissance phase.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Agent Smith is mobile malware that generates financial gain by replacing legitimate applications on devices with malicious versions that include fraudulent ads.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] As of July 2019 Agent Smith had infected around 25 million devices, primarily targeting India though effects had been observed in other Asian countries as well as Saudi Arabia, the United Kingdom, and the United States.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Agent Tesla is a spyware Trojan written for the .NET framework that has been observed since at least 2014.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Agent.btz is a worm that primarily spreads itself via removable devices such as USB drives.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] It reportedly infected U.S. military networks in 2008.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] AhRat is an Android remote access tool based on the open-source AhMyth remote access tool.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] AhRat initially spread in August 2022 on the Google Play Store via an update containing malicious code to the previously benign application, "iRecorder – Screen Recorder," which itself was released in September 2021.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Akira ransomware, written in C++, is most prominently (but not exclusively) associated with the ransomware-as-a-service entity Akira.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Akira ransomware has been used in attacks across North America, Europe, and Australia, with a focus on critical infrastructure sectors including manufacturing, education, and IT services.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Akira ransomware employs hybrid encryption and threading to increase the speed and efficiency of encryption and runtime arguments for tailored attacks.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Notable variants include Rust-based Megazord for targeting Windows and Akira _v2 for targeting VMware ESXi servers.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Akira _v2 is a Rust-based variant of Akira ransomware that has been in use since at least 2024.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Akira _v2 is designed to target VMware ESXi servers and includes a new command-line argument set and other expanded capabilities.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Allwinner is a company that supplies processors used in Android tablets and other devices.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] A Linux kernel distributed by Allwinner for use on these devices reportedly contained a backdoor.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Amadey is a Trojan bot that has been used since at least October 2018.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Anchor is one of a family of backdoor malware that has been used in conjunction with TrickBot on selected high profile targets since at least 2018.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Android/AdDisplay.Ashas is a variant of adware that has been distributed through multiple apps in the Google Play Store.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Android/Chuli.A is Android malware that was delivered to activist groups via a spearphishing email with an attachment.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Android/SpyAgent is a variant of spyware in the MoqHao phishing campaign primarily targeting Korean and Japanese users.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Fake security applications were used to target Japanese users, while fake police applications were used to target Korean users.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Both fake applications have common C2 commands and share the same crash report key on a cloud service.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] AndroidOS/MalLocker.B is a variant of a ransomware family targeting Android devices.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] It prevents the user from interacting with the UI by displaying a screen containing a ransom note over all other windows.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] ANDROIDOS_ANSERVER.A is Android malware that is unique because it uses encrypted content within a blog site for command and control.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] ANDROMEDA is commodity malware that was widespread in the early 2010's and continues to be observed in infections across a wide variety of industries.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] During the 2022 C0026 campaign, threat actors re-registered expired ANDROMEDA C2 domains to spread malware to select targets in Ukraine.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] AndroRAT is an open-source remote access tool for Android devices.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] AndroRAT is capable of collecting data, such as device location, call logs, etc., and is capable of executing actions, such as sending SMS messages and taking pictures.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] It is originally available through the `The404Hacking` Github repository.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] ANELLDR, a loader that has been in use since at least 2018, was designed to decrypt and execute UPPERCUT in memory.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] ANELLDR can use anti-analysis techniques and is known to share code overlap with HiddenFace.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Anubis is Android malware that was originally used for cyber espionage, and has been retooled as a banking trojan.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Apostle is malware that has functioned as both a wiper and, in more recent versions, as ransomware.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Apostle is written in .NET and shares various programming and functional overlaps with IPsec Helper.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] AppleJeus is a family of downloaders initially discovered in 2018 embedded within trojanized cryptocurrency applications.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] AppleJeus has been used by Lazarus Group, targeting companies in the energy, finance, government, industry, technology, and telecommunications sectors, and several countries including the United States, United Kingdom, South Korea, Australia, Brazil, New Zealand, and Russia.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] AppleJeus has been used to distribute the FALLCHILL RAT.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] AppleSeed is a backdoor that has been used by Kimsuky to target South Korean government, academic, and commercial targets since at least 2021.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Aria-body is a custom backdoor that has been used by Naikon since approximately 2017.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Arp displays and modifies information about a system's Address Resolution Protocol (ARP) cache.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Asacub is a banking trojan that attempts to steal money from victims’ bank accounts.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] It attempts to do this by initiating a wire transfer via SMS message from compromised devices.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] AshTag is a modular .NET backdoor with multiple features that has been used by WIRTE since at least 2025.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] AshTag is designed for persistence and remote command execution and can masquerade as a legitimate VisualServer utility.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] It has been modified by Threat Group-3390 actors to create the ASPXTool version.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Astaroth is a Trojan and information stealer known to affect companies in Europe, Brazil, and throughout Latin America.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] It has been known publicly since at least late 2017.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] AsyncRAT is an open-source remote access tool originally available through the NYANxCAT Github repository that has been used in malicious campaigns.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] at is used to schedule tasks on a system to run at a specified date or time.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Attor is a Windows-based espionage platform that has been seen in use since 2013.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Attor has a loadable plugin architecture to customize functionality for specific targets.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] attrib is a Windows utility used to display, set or remove attributes assigned to files or directories.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] AuditCred is a malicious DLL that has been used by Lazarus Group during their 2018 attacks.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] AuTo Stealer is malware written in C++ has been used by SideCopy since at least December 2021 to target government agencies and personnel in India and Afghanistan.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] AutoIt backdoor is malware that has been used by the actors responsible for the MONSOON campaign.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] The actors frequently used it in weaponized .pps files exploiting CVE-2014-6352.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] This malware makes use of the legitimate scripting language for Windows GUI automation with the same name.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Avaddon is ransomware written in C++ that has been offered as Ransomware-as-a-Service (RaaS) since at least June 2020.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Avenger is a downloader that has been used by BRONZE BUTLER since at least 2019.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] AvosLocker is ransomware written in C++ that has been offered via the Ransomware-as-a-Service (RaaS) model.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] It was first observed in June 2021 and has been used against financial services, critical manufacturing, government facilities, and other critical infrastructure sectors in the United States.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] As of March 2022, AvosLocker had also been used against organizations in Belgium, Canada, China, Germany, Saudi Arabia, Spain, Syria, Taiwan, Turkey, the United Arab Emirates, and the United Kingdom.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Azorult is a commercial Trojan that is used to steal information from compromised hosts.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Azorult has been observed in the wild as early as 2016.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] In July 2018, Azorult was seen used in a spearphishing campaign against targets in North America.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Azorult has been seen used for cryptocurrency theft.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Babuk is a Ransomware-as-a-service (RaaS) malware that has been used since at least 2021.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] The operators of Babuk employ a "Big Game Hunting" approach to targeting major enterprises and operate a leak site to post stolen data as part of their extortion scheme.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BabyShark is a Microsoft Visual Basic (VB) script-based malware family that is believed to be associated with several North Korean campaigns.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BackConfig is a custom Trojan with a flexible plugin architecture that has been used by Patchwork.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Backdoor.Oldrea is a modular backdoor that used by Dragonfly against energy companies since at least 2013.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Backdoor.Oldrea was distributed via supply chain compromise, and included specialized modules to enumerate and map ICS-specific systems, processes, and protocols.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BACKSPACE is a backdoor used by APT30 that dates back to at least 2005.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Bad Rabbit is a self-propagating ransomware that affected the Ukrainian transportation sector in 2017.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Bad Rabbit has also targeted organizations and consumers in Russia.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BADCALL is a Trojan malware variant used by the group Lazarus Group.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BADFLICK is a backdoor used by Leviathan in spearphishing campaigns first reported in 2018 that targeted the U.S. engineering and maritime industries.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BADHATCH is a backdoor that has been utilized by FIN8 since at least 2019.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BADHATCH has been used to target the insurance, retail, technology, and chemical industries in the United States, Canada, South Africa, Panama, and Italy.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BADNEWS is malware that has been used by the actors responsible for the Patchwork campaign.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Its name was given due to its use of RSS feeds, forums, and blogs for command and control.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BadPatch is a Windows Trojan that was used in a Gaza Hackers-linked campaign.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Bandook is a commercially available RAT, written in Delphi and C++, that has been available since at least 2007.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] It has been used against government, financial, energy, healthcare, education, IT, and legal organizations in the US, South America, Europe, and Southeast Asia.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Bandook has been used by Dark Caracal, as well as in a separate campaign referred to as "Operation Manul".
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Bankshot is a remote access tool (RAT) that was first reported by the Department of Homeland Security in December of 2017.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] In 2018, Lazarus Group used the Bankshot implant in attacks against the Turkish financial sector.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Bazar is a downloader and backdoor that has been used since at least April 2020, with infections primarily against professional services, healthcare, manufacturing, IT, logistics and travel companies across the US and Europe.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Bazar reportedly has ties to TrickBot campaigns and can be used to deploy additional malware, including ransomware, and to steal sensitive data.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BBK is a downloader that has been used by BRONZE BUTLER since at least 2019.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BBSRAT is malware with remote access tool functionality that has been used in targeted compromises.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BeaverTail is a malware that has both a JavaScript and C++ variant.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Active since 2022, BeaverTail is capable of stealing logins from browsers and serves as a downloader for second stage payloads.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BeaverTail has previously been leveraged by North Korea-affiliated actors identified as DeceptiveDevelopment or Contagious Interview.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BeaverTail has been delivered to victims through code repository sites and has been embedded within malicious attachments.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BendyBear is an x64 shellcode for a stage-zero implant designed to download malware from a C2 server.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] First discovered in August 2020, BendyBear shares a variety of features with Waterbear, malware previously attributed to the Chinese cyber espionage group BlackTech.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BFG Agonizer is a wiper related to the open-source project CRYLINE-v.5.0.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] The malware is associated with wiping operations conducted by the Agrius threat actor.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Binary Validator is a Mach-O binary file used during Operation Triangulation.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Binary Validator first collects information about the device, such as the device's phone number and a list of installed applications, before the deployment of the TriangleDB implant.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] After the actions are completed and the data is collected, Binary Validator encrypts and sends the data to the C2 server, and in turn, the C2 server sends the TriangleDB implant.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BISCUIT is a backdoor that has been used by APT1 since as early as 2007.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Bisonal is a remote access tool (RAT) that has been used by Tonto Team against public and private sector organizations in Russia, South Korea, and Japan since at least December 2010.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BitPaymer is a ransomware variant first observed in August 2017 targeting hospitals in the U.K.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BitPaymer uses a unique encryption key, ransom note, and contact information for each operation.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BitPaymer has several indicators suggesting overlap with the Dridex malware and is often delivered via Dridex.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BITSAdmin is a command line tool used to create and manage BITS Jobs.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Black Basta is ransomware written in C++ that has been offered within the ransomware-as-a-service (RaaS) model since at least April 2022; there are variants that target Windows and VMWare ESXi servers.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Black Basta operations have included the double extortion technique where in addition to demanding ransom for decrypting the files of targeted organizations the cyber actors also threaten to post sensitive information to a leak site if the ransom is not paid.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Black Basta affiliates have targeted multiple high-value organizations, with the largest number of victims based in the U.S.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Based on similarities in TTPs, leak sites, payment sites, and negotiation tactics, security researchers assess the Black Basta RaaS operators could include current or former members of the Conti group.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BlackByte 2.0 Ransomware is a replacement for BlackByte Ransomware.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Unlike BlackByte Ransomware, BlackByte 2.0 Ransomware does not have a common key for victim decryption.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BlackByte 2.0 Ransomware remains uniquely associated with BlackByte operations.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BlackByte Ransomware is uniquely associated with BlackByte operations.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BlackByte Ransomware used a common key for infections, allowing for the creation of a universal decryptor.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BlackByte Ransomware was replaced in BlackByte operations by BlackByte 2.0 Ransomware by 2023.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BlackCat is ransomware written in Rust that has been offered via the Ransomware-as-a-Service (RaaS) model.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] First observed November 2021, BlackCat has been used to target multiple sectors and organizations in various countries and regions in Africa, the Americas, Asia, Australia, and Europe.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BLACKCOFFEE is malware that has been used by several Chinese groups since at least 2013.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BlackEnergy is a malware toolkit that has been used by both criminal and APT actors.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] It dates back to at least 2007 and was originally designed to create botnets for use in conducting Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS) attacks, but its use has evolved to support various plug-ins.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] It is well known for being used during the confrontation between Georgia and Russia in 2008, as well as in targeting Ukrainian institutions.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Variants include BlackEnergy 2 and BlackEnergy 3.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BlackMould is a web shell based on China Chopper for servers running Microsoft IIS.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] First reported in December 2019, it has been used in malicious campaigns by GALLIUM against telecommunication providers.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BLINDINGCAN is a remote access Trojan that has been used by the North Korean government since at least early 2020 in cyber operations against defense, engineering, and government organizations in Western Europe and the US.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BloodHound is an Active Directory (AD) reconnaissance tool that can reveal hidden relationships and identify attack paths within an AD environment.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BLUELIGHT is a remote access Trojan used by APT37 that was first observed in early 2021.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BOLDMOVE is a type of backdoor malware written in C linked to People’s Republic of China operations from 2022 through 2023.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BOLDMOVE includes both Windows and Linux variants, with some Linux variants specifically designed for FortiGate Firewall devices.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BOLDMOVE is linked to zero-day exploitation of CVE-2022-42475 in FortiOSS SSL-VPNs.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] The record for BOLDMOVE only covers known Linux variants.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Bonadan is a malicious version of OpenSSH which acts as a custom backdoor.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Bonadan has been active since at least 2018 and combines a new cryptocurrency-mining module with the same credential-stealing module used by the Onderon family of backdoors.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BONDUPDATER is a PowerShell backdoor used by OilRig.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] It was first observed in November 2017 during targeting of a Middle Eastern government organization, and an updated version was observed in August 2018 being used to target a government organization with spearphishing emails.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BOOKWORM is a modular trojan known to be leveraged by Mustang Panda and was first observed utilized in 2015.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BOOKWORM was later updated in late 2021 and the fall of 2022 to launch shellcode represented as UUID parameters.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BoomBox is a downloader responsible for executing next stage components that has been used by APT29 since at least 2021.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BOOSTWRITE is a loader crafted to be launched via abuse of the DLL search order of applications used by FIN7.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BOOTRASH is a Bootkit that targets Windows operating systems.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] It has been used by threat actors that target the financial sector.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BOULDSPY is an Android malware, detected in early 2023, with surveillance and remote-control capabilities.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Analysis of exfiltrated C2 data suggests that BOULDSPY primarily targeted minority groups in Iran.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BoxCaon is a Windows backdoor that was used by IndigoZebra in a 2021 spearphishing campaign against Afghan government officials.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BoxCaon's name stems from similarities shared with the malware family xCaon.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BPFDoor is a Linux based passive long-term backdoor used by China-based threat actors.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] First seen in 2021, BPFDoor is named after its usage of Berkley Packet Filter (BPF) to execute single task instructions.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BPFDoor supports multiple protocols for communicating with a C2 including TCP, UDP, and ICMP and can start local or reverse shells that bypass firewalls using iptables.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BrainTest is a family of Android malware.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BRATA (Brazilian Remote Access Tool, Android), is an evolving Android malware strain, detected in late 2018 and again in late 2021.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Originating in Brazil, BRATA was later also found in the UK, Poland, Italy, Spain, and USA, where it is believed to have targeted financial institutions such as banks.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] There are currently three known variants of BRATA.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Brave Prince is a Korean-language implant that was first observed in the wild in December 2017.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] It contains similar code and behavior to Gold Dragon, and was seen along with Gold Dragon and RunningRAT in operations surrounding the 2018 Pyeongchang Winter Olympics.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Bread was a large-scale billing fraud malware family known for employing many different cloaking and obfuscation techniques in an attempt to continuously evade Google Play Store’s malware detection.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] 1,700 unique Bread apps were detected and removed from the Google Play Store before being downloaded by users.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Briba is a trojan used by Elderwood to open a backdoor and download files on to compromised hosts.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BRICKSTORM is a cross-platform backdoor with variants written in Go and Rust that facilitates command and control, the ingress transfer of other malware, and the exfiltration of data.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BRICKSTORM has also been created from a .NET application using ahead-of-time (AOT) compilation to blend in within victim environments.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BRICKSTORM was first observed in April 2024.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BRICKSTORM has previously been leveraged by People's Republic of China (PRC) state-nexus actors identified as UNC6201, UNC5221, WARP PANDA, PunyToad, and SYLVANITE.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BRUSHFIRE is a passive backdoor written in C that executes in-memory within an existing process.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] First reported in March 2025, BRUSHFIRE has been observed in activity attributed to People's Republic of China (PRC) state-affiliated threat actors, including UNC5221 and SYLVANITE.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Brute Ratel C4 is a commercial red-teaming and adversarial attack simulation tool that first appeared in December 2020.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Brute Ratel C4 was specifically designed to avoid detection by endpoint detection and response (EDR) and antivirus (AV) capabilities, and deploys agents called badgers to enable arbitrary command execution for lateral movement, privilege escalation, and persistence.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] In September 2022, a cracked version of Brute Ratel C4 was leaked in the cybercriminal underground, leading to its use by threat actors.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BS2005 is malware that was used by Ke3chang in spearphishing campaigns since at least 2011.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BUBBLEWRAP is a full-featured, second-stage backdoor used by the admin@338 group.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] It is set to run when the system boots and includes functionality to check, upload, and register plug-ins that can further enhance its capabilities.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] build_downer is a downloader that has been used by BRONZE BUTLER since at least 2019.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Bumblebee is a custom loader written in C++ that has been used by multiple threat actors, including possible initial access brokers, to download and execute additional payloads since at least March 2022.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Bumblebee has been linked to ransomware operations including Conti, Quantum, and Mountlocker and derived its name from the appearance of "bumblebee" in the user-agent.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Bundlore is adware written for macOS that has been in use since at least 2015.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Though categorized as adware, Bundlore has many features associated with more traditional backdoors.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BUSHWALK is a web shell written in Perl that was inserted into the legitimate querymanifest.cgi file on compromised Ivanti Connect Secure VPNs during Cutting Edge.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] BusyGasper is Android spyware that has been in use since May 2016.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] There have been less than 10 victims, all who appear to be located in Russia, that were all infected via physical access to the device.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Cachedump is a publicly-available tool that program extracts cached password hashes from a system’s registry.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CaddyWiper is a destructive data wiper that has been used in attacks against organizations in Ukraine since at least March 2022.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Cadelspy is a backdoor that has been used by APT39.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CALENDAR is malware used by APT1 that mimics legitimate Gmail Calendar traffic.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Calisto is a macOS Trojan that opens a backdoor on the compromised machine.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Calisto is believed to have first been developed in 2016.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CallMe is a Trojan designed to run on Apple OSX.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] It is based on a publicly available tool called Tiny SHell.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Caminho is a downloader that has been used by threat actors since at least 2025 to deliver various strains of malware such as XWorm.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Cannon is a Trojan with variants written in C# and Delphi.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CANONSTAGER is a loader known to be leveraged by Mustang Panda and was first observed utilized in 2025.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Mustang Panda utilizes DLL side-loading to execute within the victim environment prior to delivering a follow-on malicious encrypted payload.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CANONSTAGER leverages Thread Local Storage (TLS) and Native Windows APIs within the victim environment to elude detections.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CANONSTAGER also hides its code utilizing window procedures and message queues.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Carbanak is a full-featured, remote backdoor used by a group of the same name (Carbanak).
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] It is intended for espionage, data exfiltration, and providing remote access to infected machines.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Carberp is a credential and information stealing malware that has been active since at least 2009.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Carberp's source code was leaked online in 2013, and subsequently used as the foundation for the Carbanak backdoor.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Carbon is a sophisticated, second-stage backdoor and framework that can be used to steal sensitive information from victims.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Carbon has been selectively used by Turla to target government and foreign affairs-related organizations in Central Asia.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CarbonSteal is one of a family of four surveillanceware tools that share a common C2 infrastructure.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CarbonSteal primarily deals with audio surveillance.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Cardinal RAT is a potentially low volume remote access trojan (RAT) observed since December 2015.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Cardinal RAT is notable for its unique utilization of uncompiled C# source code and the Microsoft Windows built-in csc.exe compiler.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CARROTBALL is an FTP downloader utility that has been in use since at least 2019.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CARROTBALL has been used as a downloader to install SYSCON.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CARROTBAT is a customized dropper that has been in use since at least 2017.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CARROTBAT has been used to install SYSCON and has infrastructure overlap with KONNI.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CASTLETAP is an ICMP port knocking backdoor that has been installed on compromised FortiGate firewalls by UNC3886.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Catchamas is a Windows Trojan that steals information from compromised systems.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Caterpillar WebShell is a self-developed Web Shell tool created by the group Volatile Cedar.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CCBkdr is malware that was injected into a signed version of CCleaner and distributed from CCleaner's distribution website.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] ccf32 is data collection malware that has been used since at least February 2019, most notably during the FunnyDream campaign; there is also a similar x64 version.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Cerberus is a banking trojan whose usage can be rented on underground forums and marketplaces.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Prior to being available to rent, the authors of Cerberus claim was used in private operations for two years.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] certutil is a command-line utility that can be used to obtain certificate authority information and configure Certificate Services.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Chaes is a multistage information stealer written in several programming languages that collects login credentials, credit card numbers, and other financial information.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Chaes was first observed in 2020, and appears to primarily target victims in Brazil as well as other e-commerce customers in Latin America.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Chameleon is an Android banking trojan that can leverage Android’s Accessibility Services to perform malicious activities.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Believed to have been first active in January 2023, Chameleon has been observed targeting users in Australia and Poland by masquerading as official applications.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] A new variant of Chameleon has expanded its targets to include Android users in the United Kingdom and Italy.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Chaos is Linux malware that compromises systems by brute force attacks against SSH services.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Once installed, it provides a reverse shell to its controllers, triggered by unsolicited packets.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Charger is Android malware that steals steals contacts and SMS messages from the user's device.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] It can also lock the device and demand ransom payment if it receives admin permissions.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CharmPower is a PowerShell-based, modular backdoor that has been used by Magic Hound since at least 2022.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] ChChes is a Trojan that appears to be used exclusively by menuPass.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] It was used to target Japanese organizations in 2016.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Its lack of persistence methods suggests it may be intended as a first-stage tool.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Cheerscrypt is a ransomware that was developed by Cinnamon Tempest and has been used in attacks against ESXi and Windows environments since at least 2022.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Cheerscrypt was derived from the leaked Babuk source code and has infrastructure overlaps with deployments of Night Sky ransomware, which was also derived from Babuk.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CHEMISTGAMES is a modular backdoor that has been deployed by Sandworm Team.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Cherry Picker is a point of sale (PoS) memory scraper.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CherryBlos is an Android malware that steals credentials and redirects cryptocurrency to adversary-controlled wallets.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CherryBlos was labelled Robot 999 in its first appearance in April 2023; since then, various aliases have been used, including GPTalk, Happy Miner, and SynthNet.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] The threat actors behind CherryBlos uploaded the malware to different Google Play regions, such as Malaysia, Vietnam, Indonesia, Philippines, Uganda, and Mexico.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CHIMNEYSWEEP is a backdoor malware that was deployed during HomeLand Justice along with ROADSWEEP ransomware, and has been used to target Farsi and Arabic speakers since at least 2012.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] China Chopper is a Web Shell hosted on Web servers to provide access back into an enterprise network that does not rely on an infected system calling back to a remote command and control server.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] It has been used by several threat groups.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Chinoxy is a backdoor that has been used since at least November 2018, during the FunnyDream campaign, to gain persistence and drop additional payloads.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] According to security researchers, Chinoxy has been used by Chinese-speaking threat actors.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CHOPSTICK is a malware family of modular backdoors used by APT28.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] It has been used since at least 2012 and is usually dropped on victims as second-stage malware, though it has been used as first-stage malware in several cases.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] It is tracked separately from the X-Agent for Android.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Chrommme is a backdoor tool written using the Microsoft Foundation Class (MFC) framework that was first reported in June 2021; security researchers noted infrastructure overlaps with Gelsemium malware.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] cipher.exe is a native Microsoft utility that manages encryption of directories and files on NTFS (New Technology File System) partitions by using the Encrypting File System (EFS).
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Circles reportedly takes advantage of Signaling System 7 (SS7) weaknesses, the protocol suite used to route phone calls, to both track the location of mobile devices and intercept voice calls and SMS messages.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] It can be connected to a telecommunications company’s infrastructure or purchased as a cloud service.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Circles has reportedly been linked to the NSO Group.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CLAIMLOADER is a malware variant that frequently accompanies legitimate executables that are used for DLL side-loading known to be leveraged by Mustang Panda and was first observed utilized in 2021.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Clambling is a modular backdoor written in C++ that has been used by Threat Group-3390 since at least 2017.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Clop is a variant of the CryptoMix ransomware.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CloudDuke is malware that was used by APT29 in 2015.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] cmd is the Windows command-line interpreter that can be used to interact with systems and execute other processes and utilities.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Cmd.exe contains native functionality to perform many operations to interact with the system, including listing files in a directory (e.g., `dir` ), deleting files (e.g., `del` ), and copying files (e.g., `copy` ).
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] COATHANGER is a remote access tool (RAT) targeting FortiGate networking appliances.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] First used in 2023 in targeted intrusions against military and government entities in the Netherlands along with other victims, COATHANGER was disclosed in early 2024, with a high confidence assessment linking this malware to a state-sponsored entity in the People's Republic of China.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] COATHANGER is delivered after gaining access to a FortiGate device, with in-the-wild observations linked to exploitation of CVE-2022-42475.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] The name COATHANGER is based on a unique string in the malware used to encrypt configuration files on disk: `"She took his coat and hung it up"`.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Cobalt Strike is a commercial, full-featured, remote access tool that bills itself as "adversary simulation software designed to execute targeted attacks and emulate the post-exploitation actions of advanced threat actors".
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Cobalt Strike’s interactive post-exploit capabilities cover the full range of ATT&CK tactics, all executed within a single, integrated system.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] In addition to its own capabilities, Cobalt Strike leverages the capabilities of other well-known tools such as Metasploit and Mimikatz.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Cobian RAT is a backdoor, remote access tool that has been observed since 2016.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CoinTicker is a malicious application that poses as a cryptocurrency price ticker and installs components of the open source backdoors EvilOSX and EggShell.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Comnie is a remote backdoor which has been used in attacks in East Asia.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] ComRAT is a second stage implant suspected of being a descendant of Agent.btz and used by Turla.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] The first version of ComRAT was identified in 2007, but the tool has undergone substantial development for many years since.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Concipit1248 is iOS spyware that was discovered using the same name as the developer of the Android spyware Corona Updates.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Further investigation revealed that the two pieces of software contained the same C2 URL and similar functionality.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Conficker is a computer worm first detected in October 2008 that targeted Microsoft Windows using the MS08-067 Windows vulnerability to spread.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] In 2016, a variant of Conficker made its way on computers and removable disk drives belonging to a nuclear power plant.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] ConnectWise is a legitimate remote administration tool that has been used since at least 2016 by threat actors including MuddyWater and GOLD SOUTHFIELD to connect to and conduct lateral movement in target environments.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Conti is a Ransomware-as-a-Service (RaaS) that was first observed in December 2019.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Conti has been deployed via TrickBot and used against major corporations and government agencies, particularly those in North America.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] As with other ransomware families, actors using Conti steal sensitive files and information from compromised networks, and threaten to publish this data unless the ransom is paid.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CookieMiner is mac-based malware that targets information associated with cryptocurrency exchanges as well as enabling cryptocurrency mining on the victim system itself.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] It was first discovered in the wild in 2019.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CORALDECK is an exfiltration tool used by APT37.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CORESHELL is a downloader used by APT28.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] The older versions of this malware are known as SOURFACE and newer versions as CORESHELL.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CorKLOG is a keylogger known to be leveraged by Mustang Panda and was first observed utilized in 2024.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CorKLOG is delivered through a RAR archive (e.g., src.rar), which contains two files: an executable (lcommute.exe) and the CorKLOG DLL (mscorsvc.dll).
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CorKLOG has established persistence on the system by creating services or with scheduled tasks.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Corona Updates is Android spyware that took advantage of the Coronavirus pandemic.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] The campaign distributing this spyware is tracked as Project Spy.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Multiple variants of this spyware have been discovered to have been hosted on the Google Play Store.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CosmicDuke is malware that was used by APT29 from 2010 to 2015.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CostaBricks is a loader that was used to deploy 32-bit backdoors in the CostaRicto campaign.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Covenant is a multi-platform command and control framework written in .NET.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] While designed for penetration testing and security research, the tool has also been used by threat actors such as HAFNIUM during operations.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Covenant functions through a central listener managing multiple deployed "Grunts" that communicate back to the controller.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CozyCar is malware that was used by APT29 from 2010 to 2015.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] It is a modular malware platform, and its backdoor component can be instructed to download and execute a variety of modules with different functionality.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CrackMapExec, or CME, is a post-exploitation tool developed in Python and designed for penetration testing against networks.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CrackMapExec collects Active Directory information to conduct lateral movement through targeted networks.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CreepyDrive is a custom implant has been used by POLONIUM since at least early 2022 for C2 with and exfiltration to actor-controlled OneDrive accounts.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] POLONIUM has used a similar implant called CreepyBox that relies on actor-controlled DropBox accounts.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CreepySnail is a custom PowerShell implant that has been used by POLONIUM since at least 2022.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Crimson is a remote access Trojan that has been used by Transparent Tribe since at least 2016.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Crocodilus is an Android banking Trojan that was discovered in March 2025.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Crocodilus targeted users worldwide, including Turkey, Poland, Argentina, Brazil, Spain, the United States, Indonesia and India.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Crocodilus has been customized based on the target location.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] For example, Crocodilus mimicked major Turkish and Spanish banks for users in Turkey and Spain, while users in Poland saw Facebook advertisements that promoted Crocodilus to claim bonus points.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Crutch is a backdoor designed for document theft that has been used by Turla since at least 2015.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Cryptoistic is a backdoor, written in Swift, that has been used by Lazarus Group.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] CSPY Downloader is a tool designed to evade analysis and download additional payloads used by Kimsuky.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Cuba is a Windows-based ransomware family that has been used against financial institutions, technology, and logistics organizations in North and South America as well as Europe since at least December 2019.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Cuckoo Stealer is a macOS malware with characteristics of spyware and an infostealer that has been in use since at least 2024.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Cuckoo Stealer is a universal Mach-O binary that can run on Intel or ARM-based Macs and has been spread through trojanized versions of various potentially unwanted programs or PUP's such as converters, cleaners, and uninstallers.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Cyclops Blink is a modular malware that has been used in widespread campaigns by Sandworm Team since at least 2019 to target Small/Home Office (SOHO) network devices, including WatchGuard and Asus.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Cyclops Blink is assessed to be a replacement for VPNFilter, a similar platform targeting network devices.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Dacls is a multi-platform remote access tool used by Lazarus Group since at least December 2019.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] DanBot is a first-stage remote access Trojan written in C# that has been used by HEXANE since at least 2018.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] DarkComet is a Windows remote administration tool and backdoor.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] DarkGate first emerged in 2018 and has evolved into an initial access and data gathering tool associated with various criminal cyber operations.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Written in Delphi and named "DarkGate" by its author, DarkGate is associated with credential theft, cryptomining, cryptotheft, and pre-ransomware actions.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] DarkGate use increased significantly starting in 2022 and is under active development by its author, who provides it as a Malware-as-a-Service offering.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] DarkTortilla is a highly configurable .NET-based crypter that has been possibly active since at least August 2015.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] DarkTortilla has been used to deliver popular information stealers, RATs, and payloads such as Agent Tesla, AsyncRat, NanoCore, RedLine, Cobalt Strike, and Metasploit.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] DarkWatchman is a lightweight JavaScript-based remote access tool (RAT) that avoids file operations; it was first observed in November 2021.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Daserf is a backdoor that has been used to spy on and steal from Japanese, South Korean, Russian, Singaporean, and Chinese victims.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Researchers have identified versions written in both Visual C and Delphi.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] DCHSpy is an Android spyware likely used by MuddyWater.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] DCHSpy uses political decoys and masquerades as legitimate applications, such as VPNs and banking applications, to trick victims into downloading the malware.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p01] Once downloaded, DCHSpy collects information from the device and exfiltrates the data to the command and control (C2) server.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DCRAT is a variant of the open-source AsyncRAT developed in C# with additional capabilities such as patching Microsoft’s Antimalware Scan Interface (AMSI).
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DCSrv is destructive malware that has been used by Moses Staff since at least September 2021.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Though DCSrv has ransomware-like capabilities, Moses Staff does not demand ransom or offer a decryption key.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DDKONG is a malware sample that was part of a campaign by Rancor.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DDKONG was first seen used in February 2017.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DEADEYE is a malware launcher that has been used by APT41 since at least May 2021.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DEADEYE has variants that can either embed a payload inside a compiled binary (DEADEYE.EMBED) or append it to the end of a file (DEADEYE.APPEND).
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DEADWOOD is wiper malware written in C++ using Boost libraries.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DEADWOOD was first observed in an unattributed wiping event in Saudi Arabia in 2019, and has since been incorporated into Agrius operations.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DealersChoice is a Flash exploitation framework used by APT28.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DEATHRANSOM is ransomware written in C that has been used since at least 2020, and has potential overlap with FIVEHANDS and HELLOKITTY.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DEFENSOR ID is a banking trojan capable of clearing a victim’s bank account or cryptocurrency wallet and taking over email or social media accounts.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DEFENSOR ID performs the majority of its malicious functionality by abusing Android’s accessibility service.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Dendroid is an Android remote access tool (RAT) primarily targeting Western countries.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] The RAT was available for purchase for $300 and came bundled with a utility to inject the RAT into legitimate applications.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Denis is a Windows backdoor and Trojan used by APT32.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Denis shares several similarities to the SOUNDBITE backdoor and has been used in conjunction with the Goopy backdoor.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Derusbi is malware used by multiple Chinese APT groups.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Both Windows and Linux variants have been observed.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Desert Scorpion is surveillanceware that has targeted the Middle East, specifically individuals located in Palestine.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Desert Scorpion is suspected to have been operated by the threat actor APT-C-23.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] There are multiple close variants of Desert Scorpion, such as VAMP, GnatSpy, FrozenCell and SpyC23, which add some additional functionality but are not significantly different from the original malware.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Diavol is a ransomware variant first observed in June 2021 that is capable of prioritizing file types to encrypt based on a pre-configured list of extensions defined by the attacker.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] The Diavol Ransomware-as-a Service (RaaS) program is managed by Wizard Spider and it has been observed being deployed by Bazar.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Dipsind is a malware family of backdoors that appear to be used exclusively by PLATINUM.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Disco is a custom implant that has been used by MoustachedBouncer since at least 2020 including in campaigns using targeted malicious content injection for initial access and command and control.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Diskpart is a Windows command-line utility that is used to manage the computer’s drives, which includes disks, partitions, volumes and virtual hard disks.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Adversaries may abuse Diskpart to perform discovery and destructive actions on a system’s storage.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DnsSystem is a .NET based DNS backdoor, which is a customized version of the open source tool DIG.net, that has been used by HEXANE since at least June 2022.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DocSwap is an Android malware first identified in 2025, and attributed to Kimsuky.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DocSwap’s name is a combination of its Korean name "문서열람 인증 앱" (Document Viewing Authentication App) and a phishing page masquerading as CoinSwap at the C2 address.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Based on DocSwap’s name and Korean-language strings, DocSwap potentially targets mobile device users in South Korea.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Several variants of DocSwap exist; one of the latest samples indicates that the adversary added a native decryption function that decrypts an internal APK.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DOGCALL is a backdoor used by APT37 that has been used to target South Korean government and military organizations in 2017.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] It is typically dropped using a Hangul Word Processor (HWP) exploit.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Dok is a Trojan application disguised as a .zip file that is able to collect user credentials and install a malicious proxy server to redirect a user's network traffic (i.e.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Doki is a backdoor that uses a unique Dogecoin-based Domain Generation Algorithm and was first observed in July 2020.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Doki was used in conjunction with the ngrok Mining Botnet in a campaign that targeted Docker servers in cloud platforms.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Donut is an open source framework used to generate position-independent shellcode.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Donut generated code has been used by multiple threat actors to inject and load malicious payloads into memory.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DoubleAgent is a family of RAT malware dating back to 2013, known to target groups with contentious relationships with the Chinese government.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] down_new is a downloader that has been used by BRONZE BUTLER since at least 2019.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Downdelph is a first-stage downloader written in Delphi that has been used by APT28 in rare instances between 2013 and 2015.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DOWNIISSA is a shellcode downloader that has been used by MirrorFace since at least 2022 to deploy payloads, including the LODEINFO backdoor.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DownPaper is a backdoor Trojan; its main functionality is to download and run second stage malware.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DRATzarus is a remote access tool (RAT) that has been used by Lazarus Group to target the defense and aerospace organizations globally since at least summer 2020.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DRATzarus shares similarities with Bankshot, which was used by Lazarus Group in 2017 to target the Turkish financial sector.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Dridex is a prolific banking Trojan that first appeared in 2014.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] By December 2019, the US Treasury estimated Dridex had infected computers in hundreds of banks and financial institutions in over 40 countries, leading to more than $100 million in theft.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Dridex was created from the source code of the Bugat banking Trojan (also known as Cridex).
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Drinik is an evolving Android banking trojan that was observed targeting customers of around 27 banks in India in August 2021.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Initially seen as an SMS stealer in 2016, Drinik resurfaced as a banking trojan with more advanced capabilities included in subsequent versions between September 2021 and August 2022.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DroidJack is an Android remote access tool that has been observed posing as legitimate applications including the Super Mario Run and Pokemon GO games.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DropBook is a Python-based backdoor compiled with PyInstaller.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Drovorub is a Linux malware toolset comprised of an agent, client, server, and kernel modules, that has been used by APT28.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DRYHOOK is Python script used to steal credentials.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DRYHOOK was first reported in January 2025, and has previously been leveraged by People's Republic of China (PRC) state-affiliated threat actors identified as UNC5221 and SYLVANITE.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] dsquery is a command-line utility that can be used to query Active Directory for information from a system within a domain.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] It is typically installed only on Windows Server versions but can be installed on non-server variants through the Microsoft-provided Remote Server Administration Tools bundle.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Dtrack is spyware that was discovered in 2019 and has been used against Indian financial institutions, research facilities, and the Kudankulam Nuclear Power Plant.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Dtrack shares similarities with the DarkSeoul campaign, which was attributed to Lazarus Group.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DualToy is Windows malware that installs malicious applications onto Android and iOS devices connected over USB.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Duqu is a malware platform that uses a modular approach to extend functionality after deployment within a target network.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DUSTPAN is an in-memory dropper written in C/C++ used by APT41 since 2021 that decrypts and executes an embedded payload.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DUSTTRAP is a multi-stage plugin framework associated with APT41 operations with multiple components.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DustySky is multi-stage malware written in .NET that has been used by Molerats since May 2015.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Dvmap is rooting malware that injects malicious code into system runtime libraries.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] It is credited with being the first malware that performs this type of code injection.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DynoWiper is a destructive malware associated with the 2025 Poland Wiper Attacks in December of 2025.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] DynoWiper is a native Windows binary that is distributed by a PowerShell script and overwrites files using data generated by the Mersenne Twister algorithm before they are deleted from the system.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Multiple variants of DynoWiper have been identified, with the primary differences being that one variant shuts down the system after completing its destructive operations, and another introduces a time delay between file overwriting and deletion.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Dyre is a banking Trojan that has been used for financial gain.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Ebury is an OpenSSH backdoor and credential stealer targeting Linux servers and container hosts developed by Windigo.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Ebury is primarily installed through modifying shared libraries (`.so` files) executed by the legitimate OpenSSH program.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] First seen in 2009, Ebury has been used to maintain a botnet of servers, deploy additional malware, and steal cryptocurrency wallets, credentials, and credit card details.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] ECCENTRICBANDWAGON is a remote access Trojan (RAT) used by North Korean cyber actors that was first identified in August 2020.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] It is a reconnaissance tool--with keylogging and screen capture functionality--used for information gathering on compromised systems.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Ecipekac is a multi-layer loader that has been used by menuPass since at least 2019 including use as a loader for P8RAT, SodaMaster, and FYAnti.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Egregor is a Ransomware-as-a-Service (RaaS) tool that was first observed in September 2020.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Researchers have noted code similarities between Egregor and Sekhmet ransomware, as well as Maze ransomware.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] EKANS is ransomware variant written in Golang that first appeared in mid-December 2019 and has been used against multiple sectors, including energy, healthcare, and automotive manufacturing, which in some cases resulted in significant operational disruptions.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] EKANS has used a hard-coded kill-list of processes, including some associated with common ICS software platforms (e.g., GE Proficy, Honeywell HMIWeb, etc), similar to those defined in MegaCortex.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Elise is a custom backdoor Trojan that appears to be used exclusively by Lotus Blossom.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] It is part of a larger group of tools referred to as LStudio, ST Group, and APT0LSTU.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] ELMER is a non-persistent, proxy-aware HTTP backdoor written in Delphi that has been used by APT16.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Embargo is a ransomware variant written in Rust that has been active since at least May 2024.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Embargo ransomware operations are associated with "double extortion" ransomware activity, where data is exfiltrated from victim environments prior to encryption, with threats to publish files if a ransom is not paid.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Embargo ransomware has been known to be delivered through a loader known as MDeployer which also leverages a malware component known as MS4Killer that facilitates termination of processes operating on the victim hosts.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Embargo is also reportedly a Ransomware as a Service (RaaS).
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Emissary is a Trojan that has been used by Lotus Blossom.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] It shares code with Elise, with both Trojans being part of a malware group referred to as LStudio.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Emotet is a modular malware variant which is primarily used as a downloader for other malware variants such as TrickBot and IcedID.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Emotet first emerged in June 2014, initially targeting the financial sector, and has expanded to multiple verticals over time.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Empire is an open-source, cross-platform remote administration and post-exploitation framework that is publicly available on GitHub.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] While the tool itself is primarily written in Python, the post-exploitation agents are written in pure PowerShell for Windows and Python for Linux/macOS.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Empire was one of five tools singled out by a joint report on public hacking tools being widely used by adversaries.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] EnvyScout is a dropper that has been used by APT29 since at least 2021.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Epic is a backdoor that has been used by Turla.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Escobar is an Android banking trojan, first detected in March 2021, believed to be a new variant of AbereBot.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] esentutl is a command-line tool that provides database utilities for the Windows Extensible Storage Engine.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] eSurv is mobile surveillanceware designed for the lawful intercept market that was developed over the course of many years.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] EventBot is an Android banking trojan and information stealer that abuses Android’s accessibility service to steal data from various applications.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] EventBot was designed to target over 200 different banking and financial applications, the majority of which are European bank and cryptocurrency exchange applications.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] EvilBunny is a C++ malware sample observed since 2011 that was designed to be a execution platform for Lua scripts.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] evilginx2 is an open-source adversary-in-the-middle (AiTM) attack framework based on the open-source nginx web server. evilginx2 can be used as a reverse proxy between victims and legitimate web services to intercept and capture credentials, authentication tokens, and session cookies.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] EvilGrab is a malware family with common reconnaissance capabilities.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] It has been deployed by menuPass via malicious Microsoft Office documents as part of spearphishing campaigns.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] EVILNUM is fully capable backdoor that was first identified in 2018.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] EVILNUM is used by the APT group Evilnum which has the same name.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Exaramel for Linux is a backdoor written in the Go Programming Language and compiled as a 64-bit ELF binary.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] The Windows version is tracked separately under Exaramel for Windows.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Exaramel for Windows is a backdoor used for targeting Windows systems.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] The Linux version is tracked separately under Exaramel for Linux.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Exbyte is an exfiltration tool written in Go that is uniquely associated with BlackByte operations.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Observed since 2022, Exbyte transfers collected files to online file sharing and hosting services.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Exobot is Android banking malware, primarily targeting financial institutions in Germany, Austria, and France.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Exodus is Android spyware deployed in two distinct stages named Exodus One (dropper) and Exodus Two (payload).
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Expand is a Windows utility used to expand one or more compressed CAB files.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] It has been used by BBSRAT to decompress a CAB file into executable content.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Explosive is a custom-made remote access tool used by the group Volatile Cedar.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] It was first identified in the wild in 2015.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Fakecalls is an Android trojan, first detected in January 2021, that masquerades as South Korean banking apps.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] It has capabilities to intercept calls to banking institutions and even maintain realistic dialogues with the victim using pre-recorded audio snippets.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FakeM is a shellcode-based Windows backdoor that has been used by Scarlet Mimic.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FakeSpy is Android spyware that has been operated by the Chinese threat actor behind the Roaming Mantis campaigns.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FALLCHILL is a RAT that has been used by Lazarus Group since at least 2016 to target the aerospace, telecommunications, and finance industries.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] It is usually dropped by other Lazarus Group malware or delivered when a victim unknowingly visits a compromised website.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FatDuke is a backdoor used by APT29 since at least 2016.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Felismus is a modular backdoor that has been used by Sowbug.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FELIXROOT is a backdoor that has been used to target Ukrainian victims.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Ferocious is a first stage implant composed of VBS and PowerShell scripts that has been used by WIRTE since at least 2021.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Fgdump is a Windows password hash dumper.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Final1stspy is a dropper family that has been used to deliver DOGCALL.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FinFisher is a government-grade commercial surveillance spyware reportedly sold exclusively to government agencies for use in targeted and lawful criminal investigations.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] It is heavily obfuscated and uses multiple anti-analysis techniques.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] It has other variants including Wingbird.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FIVEHANDS is a customized version of DEATHRANSOM ransomware written in C++.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FIVEHANDS has been used since at least 2021, including in Ransomware-as-a-Service (RaaS) campaigns, sometimes along with SombRAT.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FjordPhantom is a malicious Android application first discovered in September 2024 with targets in Southeast Asia, specifically Indonesia, Thailand, and Vietnam.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FjordPhantom was distributed through email and messaging applications.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Once installed, the application launches a virtualization solution to steal important information, such as bank accounts, and to manipulate the user interface.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] The malicious activity from the virtualization solution runs alongside legitimate banking applications.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Flagpro is a Windows-based, first-stage downloader that has been used by BlackTech since at least October 2020.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] It has primarily been used against defense, media, and communications companies in Japan.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Flame is a sophisticated toolkit that has been used to collect information since at least 2010, largely targeting Middle East countries.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FLASHFLOOD is malware developed by APT30 that allows propagation and exfiltration of data over removable devices.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] APT30 may use this capability to exfiltrate data across air-gaps.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FlawedAmmyy is a remote access tool (RAT) that was first seen in early 2016.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] The code for FlawedAmmyy was based on leaked source code for a version of Ammyy Admin, a remote access software.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FlawedGrace is a fully featured remote access tool (RAT) written in C++ that was first observed in late 2017.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FlexiSpy is sophisticated surveillanceware for iOS and Android.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Publicly-available, comprehensive analysis has only been found for the Android version.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FlexiSpy markets itself as a parental control and employee monitoring application.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FLIPSIDE is a simple tool similar to Plink that is used by FIN5 to maintain access to victims.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FlixOnline is an Android malware, first detected in early 2021, believed to target users of WhatsApp.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FlixOnline primarily spreads via automatic replies to a device’s incoming WhatsApp messages.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FluBot is a multi-purpose mobile banking malware that was first observed in Spain in late 2020.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] It primarily spread through European countries using a variety of SMS phishing messages in multiple languages.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] An international law enforcement operation of 11 countries eventually disrupted the spread of FluBot.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FlyTrap is an Android trojan, first detected in March 2021, that uses social engineering tactics to compromise Facebook accounts.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FlyTrap was initially detected through infected apps on the Google Play store, and is believed to have impacted over 10,000 victims across at least 140 countries.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FoggyWeb is a passive and highly-targeted backdoor capable of remotely exfiltrating sensitive information from a compromised Active Directory Federated Services (AD FS) server.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] It has been used by APT29 since at least early April 2021.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Fooder is a custom 64-bit C/C++ loader used by MuddyWater that can decrypt and reflectively load embedded payloads such as a go-socks5 proxy utility, the open-source HackBrowserData infostealer, or the MuddyViper backdoor.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Fooder has frequently masqueraded as an entertainment executable, such as the Snake game (e.g., `Snake_Game.exe`).
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Forfiles is a Windows utility commonly used in batch jobs to execute commands on one or more selected files or directories (ex: list all directories in a drive, read the first line of all files created yesterday, etc.).
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Forfiles can be executed from either the command line, Run window, or batch files/scripts.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FRAMESTING is a Python web shell that was used during Cutting Edge to embed into an Ivanti Connect Secure Python package for command execution.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FrameworkPOS is a point of sale (POS) malware used by FIN6 to steal payment card data from sytems that run physical POS devices.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FrostyGoop is a Windows-based binary written in Golang that allows for interaction with industrial control system (ICS) equipment via Modbus TCP over port 502.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FrostyGoop allows for reading and writing data to holding registers on targeted devices, manipulating the operation of systems for malicious purposes.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FrostyGoop is associated with the FrostyGoop Incident in Ukraine.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FrozenCell is the mobile component of a family of surveillanceware, with a corresponding desktop component known as KasperAgent and Micropsia.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] There are multiple close variants of FrozenCell, such as VAMP, GnatSpy, Desert Scorpion and SpyC23, which add some additional functionality but are not significantly different from the original malware.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FRP, which stands for Fast Reverse Proxy, is an openly available tool that is capable of exposing a server located behind a firewall or Network Address Translation (NAT) to the Internet.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FRP can support multiple protocols including TCP, UDP, and HTTP(S) and has been abused by threat actors to proxy command and control communications.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FruitFly is designed to spy on mac users .
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] ftp is a utility commonly available with operating systems to transfer information over the File Transfer Protocol (FTP).
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Adversaries can use it to transfer other tools onto a system or to exfiltrate data.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FunnyDream is a backdoor with multiple components that was used during the FunnyDream campaign since at least 2019, primarily for execution and exfiltration.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Fuxnet is malware designed to impact the industrial network infrastructure managing control system sensors for utility operations in Moscow.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Fuxnet is linked to an entity referred to as the Blackjack hacking group, which is assessed to be linked to Ukrainian intelligence services.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] FYAnti is a loader that has been used by menuPass since at least 2020, including to deploy QuasarRAT.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Fysbis is a Linux-based backdoor used by APT28 that dates back to at least 2014.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Gazer is a backdoor used by Turla since at least 2016.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Gelsemium is a modular malware comprised of a dropper (Gelsemine), a loader (Gelsenicine), and main (Gelsevirine) plug-ins written using the Microsoft Foundation Class (MFC) framework.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Gelsemium has been used by the Gelsemium group since at least 2014.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] GeminiDuke is malware that was used by APT29 from 2009 to 2012.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Get2 is a downloader written in C++ that has been used by TA505 to deliver FlawedGrace, FlawedAmmyy, Snatch and SDBbot.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] gh0st RAT is a remote access tool (RAT).
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] The source code is public and it has been used by multiple groups.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Ginp is an Android banking trojan that has been used to target Spanish banks.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Some of the code was taken directly from Anubis.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] GLASSTOKEN is a custom web shell used by threat actors during Cutting Edge to execute commands on compromised Ivanti Secure Connect VPNs.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] GlassWorm is a worm that propagated through supply chain attacks by compromising repository credentials from victim environments and having malicious payloads added to those compromised accounts for distribution to victims across the various development ecosystems.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] GlassWorm has numerous variants, including Rust binaries, encrypted JavaScript and a variant leveraging invisible Unicode characters that made reverse engineering difficult.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] GlassWorm has employed a unique command and control (C2) methodology using Solana blockchain.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] GlassWorm was first reported in October 2025.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] GLOOXMAIL is malware used by APT1 that mimics legitimate Jabber/XMPP traffic.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] GoBear is a Go-based backdoor that abuses legitimate, stolen certificates for defense evasion purposes.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] GoBear is exclusively linked to Kimsuky operations.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] GodFather is an Android banking malware that uses virtualization to mimic legitimate applications and abuses accessibility services and other permissions to evade detection and exfiltrate sensitive data.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] First identified in 2020, GodFather targets nearly 500 banking applications, cryptocurrency wallets, and exchanges worldwide; however, its virtualization-based attacks have primarily focused on several Turkish financial institutions.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] This capability enables threat actors to steal banking credentials and other sensitive account information.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Gold Dragon is a Korean-language, data gathering implant that was first observed in the wild in South Korea in July 2017.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Gold Dragon was used along with Brave Prince and RunningRAT in operations targeting organizations associated with the 2018 Pyeongchang Winter Olympics.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Golden Cup is Android spyware that has been used to target World Cup fans.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] GoldenEagle is a piece of Android malware that has been used in targeting of Uyghurs, Muslims, Tibetans, individuals in Turkey, and individuals in China.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Samples have been found as early as 2012.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] GoldenSpy is a backdoor malware which has been packaged with legitimate tax preparation software.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] GoldenSpy was discovered targeting organizations in China, being delivered with the "Intelligent Tax" software suite which is produced by the Golden Tax Department of Aisino Credit Information Co. and required to pay local taxes.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] GoldFinder is a custom HTTP tracer tool written in Go that logs the route a packet takes between a compromised network and a C2 server.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] It can be used to inform threat actors of potential points of discovery or logging of their actions, including C2 related to other malware.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] GoldFinder was discovered in early 2021 during an investigation into the SolarWinds Compromise by APT29.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] GoldMax is a second-stage C2 backdoor written in Go with Windows and Linux variants that are nearly identical in functionality.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] GoldMax was discovered in early 2021 during the investigation into the SolarWinds Compromise, and has likely been used by APT29 since at least mid-2019.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] GoldMax uses multiple defense evasion techniques, including avoiding virtualization execution and masking malicious traffic.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] GolfSpy is Android spyware deployed by the group Bouncing Golf.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Gomir is a Linux backdoor variant of the Go-based malware GoBear, uniquely assoicated with Kimsuky operations.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Gooligan is a malware family that runs privilege escalation exploits on Android devices and then uses its escalated privileges to steal authentication tokens that can be used to access data from many Google applications.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Gooligan has been described as part of the Ghost Push Android malware family.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Goopy is a Windows backdoor and Trojan used by APT32 and shares several similarities to another backdoor used by the group (Denis).
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Goopy is named for its impersonation of the legitimate Google Updater executable.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Gootloader is a Javascript-based infection framework that has been used since at least 2020 as a delivery method for the Gootkit banking trojan, Cobalt Strike, REvil, and others.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Gootloader operates on an "Initial Access as a Service" model and has leveraged SEO Poisoning to provide access to entities in multiple sectors worldwide including financial, military, automotive, pharmaceutical, and energy.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] GPlayed is an Android trojan with a broad range of capabilities.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Grandoreiro is a banking trojan written in Delphi that was first observed in 2016 and uses a Malware-as-a-Service (MaaS) business model.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Grandoreiro has confirmed victims in Brazil, Mexico, Portugal, and Spain.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] GravityRAT is a remote access tool (RAT) and has been in ongoing development since 2016.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Green Lambert is a modular backdoor that security researchers assess has been used by an advanced threat group referred to as Longhorn and The Lamberts.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] First reported in 2017, the Windows variant of Green Lambert may have been used as early as 2008; a macOS version was uploaded to a multiscanner service in September 2014.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] GreyEnergy is a backdoor written in C and compiled in Visual Studio.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] GreyEnergy shares similarities with the BlackEnergy malware and is thought to be the successor of it.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] GRIFFON is a JavaScript backdoor used by FIN7.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] GrimAgent is a backdoor that has been used before the deployment of Ryuk ransomware since at least 2020; it is likely used by FIN6 and Wizard Spider.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] gsecdump is a publicly-available credential dumper used to obtain password hashes and LSA secrets from Windows operating systems.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] GuLoader is a file downloader that has been used since at least December 2019 to distribute a variety of remote administration tool (RAT) malware, including NETWIRE, Agent Tesla, NanoCore, FormBook, and Parallax RAT.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Gustuff is mobile malware designed to steal users' banking and virtual currency credentials.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] H1N1 is a malware variant that has been distributed via a campaign using VBA macros to infect victims.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Although it initially had only loader capabilities, it has evolved to include information-stealing functionality.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Hacking Team UEFI Rootkit is a rootkit developed by the company Hacking Team as a method of persistence for remote access software.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HALFBAKED is a malware family consisting of multiple components intended to establish persistence in victim networks.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HAMMERTOSS is a backdoor that was used by APT29 in 2015.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Hancitor is a downloader that has been used by Pony and other information stealing malware.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Hannotog is a type of backdoor malware uniquely assoicated with Lotus Blossom operations since at least 2022.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HAPPYWORK is a downloader used by APT37 to target South Korean government and financial victims in November 2016.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HARDRAIN is a Trojan malware variant reportedly used by the North Korean government.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Havij is an automatic SQL Injection tool distributed by the Iranian ITSecTeam security company.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Havij has been used by penetration testers and adversaries.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Havoc is an open-source post-exploitation command and control (C2) framework first released on GitHub in October 2022 by C5pider (Paul Ungur), who continues to maintain and develop it with community contributors.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Havoc provides a wide range of offensive security capabilities and has been adopted by multiple threat actors to establish and maintain control over compromised systems.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HAWKBALL is a backdoor that was observed in targeting of the government sector in Central Asia.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] hcdLoader is a remote access tool (RAT) that has been used by APT18.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HDoor is malware that has been customized and used by the Naikon group.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HeartCrypt is a packer-as-a-service (PaaS) used to protect malware that has been available since at least 2024.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HeartCrypt has been used to pack a variety of malware including Lumma Stealer, Remcos, and Rhadamanthys.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] In the HeartCrypt PaaS model, customers submit malware via private messaging services and it is then packed and returned by the operator as a new binary.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HELLOKITTY is a ransomware written in C++ that shares similar code structure and functionality with DEATHRANSOM and FIVEHANDS.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HELLOKITTY has been used since at least 2020, targets have included a Polish video game developer and a Brazilian electric power company.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Helminth is a backdoor that has at least two variants - one written in VBScript and PowerShell that is delivered via a macros in Excel spreadsheets, and one that is a standalone Windows executable.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HenBox is Android malware that attempts to only execute on Xiaomi devices running the MIUI operating system.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HenBox has primarily been used to target Uyghurs, a minority Turkic ethnic group.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HermeticWiper is a data wiper that has been used since at least early 2022, primarily against Ukraine with additional activity observed in Latvia and Lithuania.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Some sectors targeted include government, financial, defense, aviation, and IT services.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HermeticWizard is a worm that has been used to spread HermeticWiper in attacks against organizations in Ukraine since at least 2022.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HexEval Loader is a hex-encoded loader that collects host data, decodes follow-on scripts and acts as a downloader for the BeaverTail malware.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HexEval Loader was first reported in April 2025.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HexEval Loader has previously been leveraged by North Korea-affiliated threat actors identified as Contagious Interview.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HexEval Loader has been delivered to victims through code repository sites utilizing typosquatting naming conventions of various npm packages.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Heyoka Backdoor is a custom backdoor--based on the Heyoka open source exfiltration tool--that has been used by Aoqin Dragon since at least 2013.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Hi-Zor is a remote access tool (RAT) that has characteristics similar to Sakula.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] It was used in a campaign named INOCNATION.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HiddenFace is a modular backdoor developed and used exclusively by MirrorFace since at least 2021.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HiddenFace can communicate both actively and passively and has been used against political and academic targets.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HiddenWasp is a Linux-based Trojan used to target systems for remote control.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] It comes in the form of a statically linked ELF binary with stdlibc++.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] It has been deployed along with Downdelph to execute and hide that malware.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Hikit is malware that has been used by Axiom for late-stage persistence and exfiltration after the initial compromise.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HilalRAT is a remote access-capable Android malware, developed and used by UNC788.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HilalRAT is capable of collecting data, such as device location, call logs, etc., and is capable of executing actions, such as activating a device's camera and microphone.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Hildegard is malware that targets misconfigured kubelets for initial access and runs cryptocurrency miner operations.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] The malware was first observed in January 2021.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] The TeamTNT activity group is believed to be behind Hildegard.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HIUPAN (aka U2DiskWatch) is a is a worm that propagates through removable drives known to be leveraged by Mustang Panda and was first observed utilized in 2024.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HOMEFRY is a 64-bit Windows password dumper/cracker that has previously been used in conjunction with other Leviathan backdoors.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HOPLIGHT is a backdoor Trojan that has reportedly been used by the North Korean government.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Hornbill is one of two mobile malware families known to be used by the APT Confucius.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Analysis suggests that Hornbill was first active in early 2018.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] While Hornbill and Sunbird overlap in core capabilities, Hornbill has tools and behaviors suggesting more passive reconnaissance.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HotCroissant is a remote access trojan (RAT) attributed by U.S. government entities to malicious North Korean government cyber activity, tracked collectively as HIDDEN COBRA.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HotCroissant shares numerous code similarities with Rifdoor.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HTRAN is a tool that proxies connections through intermediate hops and aids users in disguising their true geographical location.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] It can be used by adversaries to hide their location when interacting with the victim networks.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HTTPBrowser is malware that has been used by several threat groups.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] httpclient is malware used by Putter Panda.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] It is a simple tool that provides a limited range of functionality, suggesting it is likely used as a second-stage or supplementary/backup tool.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HTTPTroy is a highly obfuscated backdoor that facilitates collection, command and control, defense evasion and exfiltration.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HTTPTroy was first reported in October 2025.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HTTPTroy has been observed in operations attributed to DPRK-affiliated threat actors, including Kimsuky.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HTTPTroy has been delivered to victims through a separate loader leveraged by Kimsuky.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HUI Loader is a custom DLL loader that has been used since at least 2015 by China-based threat groups including Cinnamon Tempest and menuPass to deploy malware on compromised hosts.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HUI Loader has been observed in campaigns loading SodaMaster, PlugX, Cobalt Strike, Komplex, and several strains of ransomware.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HummingBad is a family of Android malware that generates fraudulent advertising revenue and has the ability to obtain root access on older, vulnerable versions of Android.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HummingWhale is an Android malware family that performs ad fraud.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Hydraq is a data-theft trojan first used by Elderwood in the 2009 Google intrusion known as Operation Aurora, though variations of this trojan have been used in more recent campaigns by other Chinese actors, possibly including APT17.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HyperBro is a custom in-memory backdoor used by Threat Group-3390.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HyperStack is a RPC-based backdoor used by Turla since at least 2018.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] HyperStack has similarities to other backdoors used by Turla including Carbon.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] IceApple is a modular Internet Information Services (IIS) post-exploitation framework, that has been used since at least 2021 against the technology, academic, and government sectors.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] IcedID is a modular banking malware designed to steal financial information that has been observed in the wild since at least 2017.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] IcedID has been downloaded by Emotet in multiple campaigns.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] ifconfig is a Unix-based utility used to gather information about and interact with the TCP/IP settings on a system.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] IMAPLoader is a .NET-based loader malware exclusively associated with CURIUM operations since at least 2022.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] IMAPLoader leverages email protocols for command and control and payload delivery.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Imminent Monitor was a commodity remote access tool (RAT) offered for sale from 2012 until 2019, when an operation was conducted to take down the Imminent Monitor infrastructure.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Various cracked versions and variations of this RAT are still in circulation.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Impacket is an open source collection of modules written in Python for programmatically constructing and manipulating network protocols.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Impacket contains several tools for remote service execution, Kerberos manipulation, Windows credential dumping, packet sniffing, and relay attacks.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] INC Ransomware is a ransomware strain that has been used by the INC Ransom group since at least 2023 against multiple industry sectors worldwide.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] INC Ransomware can employ partial encryption combined with multi-threading to speed encryption.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] INCONTROLLER is custom malware that includes multiple modules tailored towards ICS devices and technologies, including Schneider Electric and Omron PLCs as well as OPC UA, Modbus, and CODESYS protocols.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] INCONTROLLER has the ability to discover specific devices, download logic on the devices, and exploit platform-specific vulnerabilities.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] As of September 2022, some security researchers assessed INCONTROLLER was developed by CHERNOVITE.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Industroyer is a sophisticated malware framework designed to cause an impact to the working processes of Industrial Control Systems (ICS), specifically components used in electrical substations.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Industroyer was used in the attacks on the Ukrainian power grid in December 2016.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] This is the first publicly known malware specifically designed to target and impact operations in the electric grid.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Industroyer2 is a compiled and static piece of malware that has the ability to communicate over the IEC-104 protocol.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] It is similar to the IEC-104 module found in Industroyer.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Security researchers assess that Industroyer2 was designed to cause impact to high-voltage electrical substations.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] The initial Industroyer2 sample was compiled on 03/23/2022 and scheduled to execute on 04/08/2022, however it was discovered before deploying, resulting in no impact.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] InnaputRAT is a remote access tool that can exfiltrate files from a victim’s machine.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] InnaputRAT has been seen out in the wild since 2016.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] INSOMNIA is spyware that has been used by the group Evil Eye.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] InvisibleFerret is a modular python malware that is leveraged for data exfiltration and remote access capabilities.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] InvisibleFerret consists of four modules: main, payload, browser, and AnyDesk.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] InvisibleFerret malware has been leveraged by North Korea-affiliated threat actors identified as DeceptiveDevelopment or Contagious Interview since 2023.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] InvisibleFerret has historically been introduced to the victim environment through the use of the BeaverTail malware.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] InvisiMole is a modular spyware program that has been used by the InvisiMole Group since at least 2013.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] InvisiMole has two backdoor modules called RC2FM and RC2CL that are used to perform post-exploitation activities.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] It has been discovered on compromised victims in the Ukraine and Russia.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Gamaredon Group infrastructure has been used to download and execute InvisiMole against a small number of victims.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Invoke-PSImage takes a PowerShell script and embeds the bytes of the script into the pixels of a PNG image.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] It generates a one liner for executing either from a file of from the web.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Example of usage is embedding the PowerShell code from the Invoke-Mimikatz module and embed it into an image file.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] By calling the image file from a macro for example, the macro will download the picture and execute the PowerShell code, which in this case will dump the passwords.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] ipconfig is a Windows utility that can be used to find information about a system's TCP/IP, DNS, DHCP, and adapter configuration.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] IPsec Helper is a post-exploitation remote access tool linked to Agrius operations.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] This malware shares significant programming and functional overlaps with Apostle ransomware, also linked to Agrius.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] IPsec Helper provides basic remote access tool functionality such as uploading files from victim systems, running commands, and deploying additional payloads.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] IronNetInjector is a Turla toolchain that utilizes scripts from the open-source IronPython implementation of Python with a .NET injector to drop one or more payloads including ComRAT.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] IronWind is a custom loader malware that has been in use since at least 2023 by actors including WIRTE to target entities in the Middle East.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] ISMInjector is a Trojan used to install another OilRig backdoor, ISMAgent.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Ixeshe is a malware family that has been used since at least 2009 against targets in East Asia.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] J-magic is a custom variant of the cd00r backdoor tailored to target Juniper routers that was first observed during the J-magic Campaign in mid-2023.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] J-magic monitors TCP traffic for five predefined parameters or "magic packets" to be sent by the attackers before activating on compromised devices.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Janicab is an OS X trojan that relied on a valid developer ID and oblivious users to install it.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Javali is a banking trojan that has targeted Portuguese and Spanish-speaking countries since 2017, primarily focusing on customers of financial institutions in Brazil and Mexico.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] It was identified as apart of the #OpJerusalem 2019 campaign.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] It is based on Carberp source code and serves as reconnaissance malware.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] JPIN is a custom-built backdoor family used by PLATINUM.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Evidence suggests developers of JPIN and Dipsind code bases were related in some way.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] jRAT is a cross-platform, Java-based backdoor originally available for purchase in 2012.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Variants of jRAT have been distributed via a software-as-a-service platform, similar to an online subscription model.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] JSS Loader is Remote Access Trojan (RAT) with .NET and C++ variants that has been used by FIN7 since at least 2020.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p02] Judy is auto-clicking adware that was distributed through multiple apps in the Google Play Store.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] JumbledPath is a custom-built utility written in GO that has been used by Salt Typhoon since at least 2024 for packet capture on remote Cisco devices.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] JumbledPath is compiled as an ELF binary using x86-64 architecture which makes it potentially useable across Linux operating systems and network devices from multiple vendors.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Kapeka is a backdoor written in C++ used against victims in Eastern Europe since at least mid-2022.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Kapeka has technical overlaps with Exaramel for Windows and Prestige malware variants, both of which are linked to Sandworm Team.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Kapeka may have been used in advance of Prestige deployment in late 2022.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] KARAE is a backdoor typically used by APT37 as first-stage malware.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Kasidet is a backdoor that has been dropped by using malicious VBA macros.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Kazuar is a fully featured, multi-platform backdoor Trojan written using the Microsoft .NET framework.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Kerrdown is a custom downloader that has been used by APT32 since at least 2018 to install spyware from a server on the victim's network.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Kessel is an advanced version of OpenSSH which acts as a custom backdoor, mainly acting to steal credentials and function as a bot.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Kessel has been active since its C2 domain began resolving in August 2018.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Kevin is a backdoor implant written in C++ that has been used by HEXANE since at least June 2020, including in operations against organizations in Tunisia.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] KeyBoy is malware that has been used in targeted campaigns against members of the Tibetan Parliament in 2016.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] This piece of malware steals the content of the user's keychain while maintaining a permanent backdoor .
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] KEYMARBLE is a Trojan that has reportedly been used by the North Korean government.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] KEYPLUG is a modular backdoor written in C++, with Windows and Linux variants, that has been used by APT41 since at least June 2021.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] KeyRaider is malware that steals Apple account credentials and other data from jailbroken iOS devices.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] KGH_SPY is a modular suite of tools used by Kimsuky for reconnaissance, information stealing, and backdoor capabilities.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] KGH_SPY derived its name from PDB paths and internal names found in samples containing "KGH".
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] KillDisk is a disk-wiping tool designed to overwrite files with random data to render the OS unbootable.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] It was first observed as a component of BlackEnergy malware during cyber attacks against Ukraine in 2015.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] KillDisk has since evolved into stand-alone malware used by a variety of threat actors against additional targets in Europe and Latin America; in 2016 a ransomware component was also incorporated into some KillDisk variants.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Kinsing is Golang-based malware that runs a cryptocurrency miner and attempts to spread itself to other hosts in the victim environment.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Kivars is a modular remote access tool (RAT), derived from the Bifrost RAT, that was used by BlackTech in a 2010 campaign.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Koadic is a Windows post-exploitation framework and penetration testing tool that is publicly available on GitHub.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Koadic has several options for staging payloads and creating implants, and performs most of its operations using Windows Script Host.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Kobalos is a multi-platform backdoor that can be used against Linux, FreeBSD, and Solaris.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Kobalos has been deployed against high profile targets, including high-performance computers, academic servers, an endpoint security vendor, and a large internet service provider; it has been found in Europe, North America, and Asia.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Kobalos was first identified in late 2019.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] KOCTOPUS's batch variant is loader used by LazyScripter since 2018 to launch Octopus and Koadic and, in some cases, QuasarRAT.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] KOCTOPUS also has a VBA variant that has the same functionality as the batch version.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Komplex is a backdoor that has been used by APT28 on OS X and appears to be developed in a similar manner to XAgentOSX .
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] KOMPROGO is a signature backdoor used by APT32 that is capable of process, file, and registry management.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] KONNI is a remote access tool that security researchers assess has been used by North Korean cyber actors since at least 2014.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] KONNI has significant code overlap with the NOKKI malware family, and has been linked to several suspected North Korean campaigns targeting political organizations in Russia, East Asia, Europe and the Middle East; there is some evidence potentially linking KONNI to APT37.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] KOPILUWAK is a JavaScript-based reconnaissance tool that has been used for victim profiling and C2 since at least 2017.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Kwampirs is a backdoor Trojan used by Orangeworm.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Kwampirs has been found on machines which had software installed for the use and control of high-tech imaging devices such as X-Ray and MRI machines.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Kwampirs has multiple technical overlaps with Shamoon based on reverse engineering analysis.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LAMEHUG is Python-based information stealer first identified in July 2025 by Ukraine's Computer Emergency Response Team (CERT-UA) in phishing emails targeting Ukrainian government officials.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LAMEHUG is the first known malware to integrate artificial intelligence (AI) directly into its attack workflow by querying large language models (LLMs) hosted on Hugging Face to dynamically generate reconnaissance, data theft, and system manipulation commands in real time.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Latrodectus is a Windows malware downloader that has been used since at least 2023 to download and execute additional payloads and modules.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Latrodectus has most often been distributed through email campaigns, primarily by TA577 and TA578, and has infrastructure overlaps with historic IcedID operations.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LaZagne is a post-exploitation, open-source tool used to recover stored passwords on a system.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] It has modules for Windows, Linux, and OSX, but is mainly focused on Windows systems.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LaZagne is publicly available on GitHub.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LazyWiper is a destructive malware observed targeting a manufacturing sector company during the 2025 Poland Wiper Attacks.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LazyWiper is a native Windows PowerShell script that is believed to have been generated by a large language model (LLM).
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LazyWiper overwrites files on the system using the C# function `WriteRandomBytes()` and can target multiple specific file types by their extensions.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LightNeuron is a sophisticated backdoor that has targeted Microsoft Exchange servers since at least 2014.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LightNeuron has been used by Turla to target diplomatic and foreign affairs-related organizations.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] The presence of certain strings in the malware suggests a Linux variant of LightNeuron exists.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] First observed in 2018, LightSpy is a modular malware family that initially targeted iOS devices in Southern Asia before expanding to Android and macOS platforms.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] It consists of a downloader, a main executable that manages network communications, and functionality-specific modules, typically implemented as `.dylib` files (iOS, macOS) or `.apk` files (Android).
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LightSpy can collect VoIP call recordings, SMS messages, and credential stores, which are then exfiltrated to a command and control (C2) server.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LIGHTWIRE is a web shell written in Perl that was used during Cutting Edge to maintain access and enable command execution by imbedding into the legitimate compcheckresult.cgi component of Ivanti Secure Connect VPNs.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Line Dancer is a memory-only Lua-based shellcode loader associated with the ArcaneDoor campaign.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Line Dancer allows an adversary to upload and execute arbitrary shellcode on victim devices.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Line Runner is a persistent backdoor and web shell allowing threat actors to upload and execute arbitrary Lua scripts.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Line Runner is associated with the ArcaneDoor campaign.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Linfo is a rootkit trojan used by Elderwood to open a backdoor on compromised hosts.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Linux Rabbit is malware that targeted Linux servers and IoT devices in a campaign lasting from August to October 2018.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] It shares code with another strain of malware known as Rabbot.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] The goal of the campaign was to install cryptocurrency miners onto the targeted servers and devices.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LiteDuke is a third stage backdoor that was used by APT29, primarily in 2014-2015.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LiteDuke used the same dropper as PolyglotDuke, and was found on machines also compromised by MiniDuke.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LitePower is a downloader and second stage malware that has been used by WIRTE since at least 2021.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LITTLELAMB.WOOLTEA is a backdoor that was used by UNC5325 during Cutting Edge to deploy malware on targeted Ivanti Connect Secure VPNs and to establish persistence across system upgrades and patches.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Lizar is a modular remote access tool written using the .NET Framework that shares structural similarities to Carbanak.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] It has likely been used by FIN7 since at least February 2021.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LockBit 2.0 is an affiliate-based Ransomware-as-a-Service (RaaS) that has been in use since at least June 2021 as the successor to LockBit Ransomware.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LockBit 2.0 has versions capable of infecting Windows and VMware ESXi virtual machines, and has been observed targeting multiple industry verticals globally.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LockBit 3.0 is an evolution of the LockBit Ransomware-as-a-Service (RaaS) offering with similarities to BlackMatter and BlackCat ransomware.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LockBit 3.0 has been in use since at least June 2022 and features enhanced defense evasion and exfiltration tactics, robust encryption methods for Windows and VMware ESXi systems, and a more refined RaaS structure over its predecessors such as LockBit 2.0.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LockerGoga is ransomware that was first reported in January 2019, and has been tied to various attacks on European companies, including industrial and manufacturing firms.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LODEINFO is a fileless backdoor malware first identified in 2020 that has been used by actors including MirrorFace, primarily against media, diplomatic, governmental, and public sector organizations in Japan.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LoFiSe has been used by ToddyCat since at least 2023 to identify and collect files of interest on targeted systems.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LoJax is a UEFI rootkit used by APT28 to persist remote access software on targeted systems.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Lokibot is a widely distributed information stealer that was first reported in 2015.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] It is designed to steal sensitive information such as usernames, passwords, cryptocurrency wallets, and other credentials.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Lokibot can also create a backdoor into infected systems to allow an attacker to install additional payloads.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LookBack is a remote access trojan written in C++ that was used against at least three US utility companies in July 2019.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] The TALONITE activity group has been observed using LookBack.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LoudMiner is a cryptocurrency miner which uses virtualization software to siphon system resources.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] The miner has been bundled with pirated copies of Virtual Studio Technology (VST) for Windows and macOS.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] It was used in August 2015 in email messages targeting Hong Kong-based media organizations.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LP-Notes is a C/C++ Windows credential stealer used by MuddyWater.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LP-Notes was named after the `lp-notes.txt` file that is used to store stolen credentials.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Lslsass is a publicly-available tool that can dump active logon session password hashes from the lsass process.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Lucifer is a crypto miner and DDoS hybrid malware that leverages well-known exploits to spread laterally on Windows platforms.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Lumma Stealer is an information stealer malware family in use since at least 2022.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Lumma Stealer is a Malware as a Service (MaaS) where captured data has been sold in criminal markets to Initial Access Brokers.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LunarLoader is the loader component for the LunarWeb and LunarMail backdoors that has been used by Turla since at least 2020 including against a European ministry of foreign affairs (MFA).
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LunarLoader has been observed as a standalone and as a part of trojanized open-source software such as AdmPwd.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LunarMail is a backdoor that has been used by Turla since at least 2020 including in a compromise of a European ministry of foreign affairs (MFA) in conjunction with LunarLoader and LunarWeb.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LunarMail is designed to be deployed on workstations and can use email messages and Steganography in command and control.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LunarWeb is a backdoor that has been used by Turla since at least 2020 including in a compromise of a European ministry of foreign affairs (MFA) together with LunarLoader and LunarMail.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] LunarWeb has only been observed deployed against servers and can use Steganography to obfuscate command and control.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Lurid is a malware family that has been used by several groups, including PittyTiger, in targeted attacks as far back as 2006.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Machete is a cyber espionage toolset used by Machete.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] It is a Python-based backdoor targeting Windows machines that was first observed in 2010.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] MacMa is a macOS-based backdoor with a large set of functionalities to control and exfiltrate files from a compromised computer.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] MacMa has been observed in the wild since November 2021.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] MacMa shares command and control and unique libraries with MgBot and Nightdoor, indicating a relationship with the Daggerfly threat actor.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] MacSpy is a malware-as-a-service offered on the darkweb .
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Mafalda is a flexible interactive implant that has been used by Metador.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Security researchers assess the Mafalda name may be inspired by an Argentinian cartoon character that has been popular as a means of political commentary since the 1960s.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] MagicRAT is a remote access tool developed in C++ and exclusively used by the Lazarus Group threat actor in operations.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] MagicRAT allows for arbitrary command execution on victim machines and provides basic remote access functionality.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] MailSniper is a penetration testing tool for searching through email in a Microsoft Exchange environment for specific terms (passwords, insider intel, network architecture information, etc.).
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] It can be used by a non-administrative user to search their own email, or by an Exchange administrator to search the mailboxes of every user in a domain.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Mandrake is a sophisticated Android espionage platform that has been active in the wild since at least 2016.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Mandrake is very actively maintained, with sophisticated features and attacks that are executed with surgical precision.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Mandrake has gone undetected for several years by providing legitimate, ad-free applications with social media and real reviews to back the apps.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] The malware is only activated when the operators issue a specific command.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Mango is a first-stage backdoor written in C#/.NET that was used by OilRig during the Juicy Mix campaign.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Mango is the successor to Solar and includes additional exfiltration capabilities, the use of native APIs, and added detection evasion code.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Manjusaka is a Chinese-language intrusion framework, similar to Sliver and Cobalt Strike, with an ELF binary written in GoLang as the controller for Windows and Linux implants written in Rust.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] First identified in 2022, Manjusaka consists of multiple components, only one of which (a command and control module) is freely available.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] MarkiRAT is a remote access Trojan (RAT) compiled with Visual Studio that has been used by Ferocious Kitten since at least 2015.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Matryoshka is a malware framework used by CopyKittens that consists of a dropper, loader, and RAT.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] It has multiple versions; v1 was seen in the wild from July 2016 until January 2017. v2 has fewer commands and other minor differences.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] MazarBOT is Android malware that was distributed via SMS in Denmark in 2016.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Maze ransomware, previously known as "ChaCha", was discovered in May 2019.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] In addition to encrypting files on victim machines for impact, Maze operators conduct information stealing campaigns prior to encryption and post the information online to extort affected companies.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] MCMD is a remote access tool that provides remote command shell capability used by Dragonfly.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] MechaFlounder is a python-based remote access tool (RAT) that has been used by APT39.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] The payload uses a combination of actor developed code and code snippets freely available online in development communities.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] MEDUSA is an open-source rootkit that is capable of dynamic linker hijacking, command execution, and logging credentials.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Medusa Ransomware has been utilized in attacks since at least 2021.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Medusa Ransomware has been known to be utilized in conjunction with living off the land techniques and remote management software.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Medusa Ransomware has been used in campaigns associated with "double extortion" ransomware activity, where data is exfiltrated from victim environments prior to encryption, with threats to publish files if a ransom is not paid.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Medusa Ransomware software was initially a closed ransomware variant which later evolved to a Ransomware as a Service (RaaS).
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Medusa Ransomware has impacted victims from a diverse range of sectors within a multitude of countries, and it is assessed Medusa Ransomware is used in an opportunistic manner.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] meek is an open-source Tor plugin that tunnels Tor traffic through HTTPS connections.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] MegaCortex is ransomware that first appeared in May 2019.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] MegaCortex has mainly targeted industrial organizations.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Megazord is a Rust-based variant of Akira ransomware that has been in use since at least August 2023 to target Windows environments.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Megazord has been attributed to the Akira group based on overlapping infrastructure though is possibly not exclusive to the group.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Melcoz is a banking trojan family built from the open source tool Remote Access PC.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Melcoz was first observed in attacks in Brazil and since 2018 has spread to Chile, Mexico, Spain, and Portugal.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] MESSAGETAP is a data mining malware family deployed by APT41 into telecommunications networks to monitor and save SMS traffic from specific phone numbers, IMSI numbers, or that contain specific keywords.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] metaMain is a backdoor used by Metador to maintain long-term access to compromised machines; it has also been used to decrypt Mafalda into memory.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Metamorfo is a Latin-American banking trojan operated by a Brazilian cybercrime group that has been active since at least April 2018.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] The group focuses on targeting banks and cryptocurrency services in Brazil and Mexico.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Meteor is a wiper that was used against Iranian government organizations, including Iranian Railways, the Ministry of Roads, and Urban Development systems, in July 2021.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Meteor is likely a newer version of similar wipers called Stardust and Comet that were reportedly used by a group called "Indra" since at least 2019 against private companies in Syria.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] MgBot is a modular malware framework exclusively associated with Daggerfly operations since at least 2012.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] MgBot was developed in C++ and features a module design with multiple available plugins that have been under active development through 2024.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Micropsia is a remote access tool written in Delphi.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Milan is a backdoor implant based on DanBot that was written in Visual C++ and .NET.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Milan has been used by HEXANE since at least June 2020.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Mimikatz is a credential dumper capable of obtaining plaintext Windows account logins and passwords, along with many other features that make it useful for testing the security of networks.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] MimiPenguin is a credential dumper, similar to Mimikatz, designed specifically for Linux platforms.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Miner-C is malware that mines victims for the Monero cryptocurrency.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] It has targeted FTP servers and Network Attached Storage (NAS) devices to spread.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] MiniDuke is malware that was used by APT29 from 2010 to 2015.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] The MiniDuke toolset consists of multiple downloader and backdoor components.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] The loader has been used with other MiniDuke components as well as in conjunction with CosmicDuke and PinchDuke.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] MirageFox is a remote access tool used against Windows systems.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] It appears to be an upgraded version of a tool known as Mirage, which is a RAT believed to originate in 2012.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] MirrorStealer is a credential stealer that has been used by MirrorFace since at least 2022 to steal credentials from various applications, including browsers and email clients.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] MirrorStealer has been delivered directly into system memory via commands issued by LODEINFO.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Mis-Type is a backdoor hybrid that was used in Operation Dust Storm by 2012.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Misdat is a backdoor that was used in Operation Dust Storm from 2010 to 2011.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Mispadu is a banking trojan written in Delphi that was first observed in 2019 and uses a Malware-as-a-Service (MaaS) business model.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] This malware is operated, managed, and sold by the Malteiro cybercriminal group.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Mispadu has mainly been used to target victims in Brazil and Mexico, and has also had confirmed operations throughout Latin America and Europe.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Mivast is a backdoor that has been used by Deep Panda.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] It was reportedly used in the Anthem breach.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] MobileOrder is a Trojan intended to compromise Android mobile devices.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] MoleNet is a downloader tool with backdoor capabilities that has been observed in use since at least 2019.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Moneybird is a ransomware variant written in C++ associated with Agrius operations.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] The name "Moneybird" is contained in the malware's ransom note and as strings in the executable.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Mongall is a backdoor that has been used since at least 2013, including by Aoqin Dragon.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] Monokle is targeted, sophisticated mobile surveillanceware.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] It is developed for Android, but there are some code artifacts that suggests an iOS version may be in development.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] MoonWind is a remote access tool (RAT) that was used in 2016 to target organizations in Thailand.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] MOPSLED is a shellcode-based modular backdoor that has been used by China-nexus cyber espionage actors including UNC3886 and APT41.
[src:mitre-attack/software-p03] More_eggs is a JScript backdoor used by Cobalt Group and FIN6.
